{"title_page": "Bruce Boa", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bruce Boa\n| image = Actor_Bruce_Boa.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Andrew Bruce Boa\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1930|07|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2004|04|17|1930|07|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Surrey]], England\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1958\u20131997\n| spouse = Cherry Boa (?-2004; his death)\n| children = 3\n| relatives = [[Marion Woodman]] (sister)\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n'''Andrew Bruce Boa''' (10 July 1930&nbsp;&ndash; 17 April 2004) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[actor]], who found success playing the token [[Americans|American]] in [[United Kingdom|British]] films and television, usually playing military types. Boa's most recognizable film role is in ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]'' (1980) as [[Carlist Rieekan|General Rieekan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GeldDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA370&lpg=PA370&dq=bruce+boa+Boa's+most+recognizable+film+role+is+in+The+Empire+Strikes+Back&source=bl&ots=WS6aOHM7VO&sig=ACfU3U2g24a4z84LmHxmhJaWI1o9iZ0q9w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi4opDfjprlAhWSTcAKHaNzAe4Q6AEwCHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=bruce+boa+Boa's+most+recognizable+film+role+is+in+The+Empire+Strikes+Back&f=false|title=Quite Quite Fantastic! The Avengers for Modern Viewers|first=Michael Scott|last=Phillips|date=18 May 2018|publisher=Lulu.com|via=Google Books}}</ref> On television, his most notable role is probably as the hard-nosed American guest, Mr. Harry Hamilton, in the \"[[Waldorf Salad (Fawlty Towers)|Waldorf Salad]]\" episode of the [[BBC]] [[sitcom]] ''[[Fawlty Towers]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/99515/Our-Fawlty-memories|title=Our Fawlty memories|first=Julie|last=Carpenter|date=7 May 2009|website=Express.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBruce Boa was born on 10 July 1930 in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], the second of three children of Ila (n\u00e9e Phinn) and Andrew Boa, a clergyman. His older sister was [[Analytical psychology|Jungian analyst]] and author [[Marion Woodman]], and his younger brother was Fraser Boa, also a Jungian analyst, who died in 1992.<ref name=\"Carey\">{{cite news |last1=Carey |first1=Benedict |title=Marion Woodman, Explorer of the Feminine Mind, Dies at 89 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/19/obituaries/marion-woodman-explorer-of-the-feminine-mind-dies-at-89.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=19 July 2018}}</ref> Boa attended the [[University of Western Ontario]], graduating in 1952 with a degree in theology, then spent a brief period playing professional football for the [[Calgary Stampeders]]. After travelling through Europe, he began his acting career in England in 1958, and settled there permanently in the 1960s. In a 1959 interview he stated that he was also writing novels and film scripts;<ref name=\"Hack\">{{cite news |last1=Hack |first1=Sylvia |title=Canadian Trying His Talents |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26238963/ |work=The Gazette |date=12 November 1959 |location=Montreal, Canada|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> however, it would appear these works were not published or filmed.\n\n==Career==\nBoa's film credits include ''[[Man in the Middle (film)|Man in the Middle]]'' (1964), ''[[The Adding Machine (film)|The Adding Machine]]'' (1969), ''[[Who? (film)|Who?]]'' (1973), ''[[The Cherry Picker]]'' (1974), ''[[The Omen]]'' (1976), ''[[Silver Bears (film)|Silver Bears]]'', ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'', ''[[Carry On Emmannuelle]]'' (1978), ''[[A Touch of the Sun (1979 film)|A Touch of the Sun]]'', ''[[The London Connection]]'', ''[[A Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square (film)|A Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square]]'' (1979), ''[[Silver Dream Racer]]'' (1980), ''[[Ragtime (film)|Ragtime]]'' (1981), ''[[Octopussy]]'' (1983), ''[[Return to Oz]]'' (1985),  and ''[[Screamers (1995 film)|Screamers]]'' (1995).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba128c463|title=Bruce Boa|website=BFI}}</ref> He also played the Marine colonel in ''[[Full Metal Jacket]]'' (1987) who chastises [[Matthew Modine]]'s character over having a peace pin on his lapel while having \"Born To Kill\" written on his combat helmet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b71c59462|title=Full Metal Jacket (1987)|website=BFI}}</ref>\n\nOn television, in 1977 he appeared in ''[[Come Back, Little Sheba (1977 TV drama)|Come Back, Little Sheba]]'', an episode of ''[[Laurence Olivier Presents]]'', opposite [[Laurence Olivier]] and [[Joanne Woodward]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b737ef303|title=Come Back Little Sheba (1977)|website=BFI}}</ref> Other television credits include: ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'', ''[[Out of the Unknown]]'', ''[[The Champions]]'', ''[[The Troubleshooters]]'', ''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'', ''[[Ace of Wands (TV series)|Ace of Wands]]'', ''[[Special Branch (TV series)|Special Branch]]'', ''[[The Onedin Line]]'', ''[[Z-Cars]]'', ''[[The New Avengers (TV series)|The New Avengers]]'', ''[[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]'', ''[[The Omega Factor]]'', ''[[Dempsey & Makepeace]]'', ''[[Astronauts (TV series)|Astronauts]]'', ''[[Hart to Hart]]'', ''[[Remington Steele]]'', ''[[Howards' Way]]'', the 1979 miniseries ''A Man Called Intrepid'', the 1988 television film ''[[The Bourne Identity (1988 film)|The Bourne Identity]]'',  ''[[Tales of the Unexpected (TV series)|Tales of the Unexpected]]'', ''[[As Time Goes By (UK TV series)|As Time Goes By]]'', ''[[Road to Avonlea]]'', ''[[Kavanagh QC]]'', ''[[Bulman]]'' and ''[[Warship (1973 TV series)|Warship]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=1708|title=Bruce Boa|website=www.aveleyman.com}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nBoa died from [[cancer]] on 17 April 2004 in [[Surrey]], England.<ref name=\"Lentz\">{{cite book |last1=Lentz |first1=Harris M. |title=Obituaries in the Performing Arts, 2004: Film, Television, Radio, Theatre, Dance, Music, Cartoons and Pop Culture |date=2008 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9780786452095 |pages=46\u201347 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=anvGCwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA46&dq=%22bruce%20boa%22&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q=%22bruce%20boa%22&f=false |language=en}}</ref> He was survived by his British wife Cherry and their three children. He was also good friends with [[John Cleese]].\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1960\n| ''[[Man in the Moon (film)|Man in the Moon]]''\n| Roy\n| Film debut\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[Man in the Middle (film)|Man in the Middle]]''\n| Maj. Lawson\n|\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''[[The Mini-Affair]]''\n| American Newman\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1969\n| ''[[Can Heironymus Merkin Ever Forget Mercy Humppe and Find True Happiness?]]''\n| Car Salesman\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| ''[[The Adding Machine (film)|The Adding Machine]]''\n| Detective\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[The Revolutionary]]''\n| Guest at Party\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Who? (film)|Who?]]''\n| Miller\n|\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[The Cherry Picker]]''\n| Dr. Softman\n|\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[The Omen]]''\n| Thorn's Aide\n|\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Silver Bears (film)|Silver Bears]]''\n| American Banker\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1978\n| ''[[Carry on Emmannuelle]]''\n| U.S. Ambassador\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]''\n| Joint chief of general staff\n| Extended version, Uncredited\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 1979\n| ''[[The London Connection]]''\n| Colonel\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Unidentified Flying Oddball]]''\n| Air Force Officer\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| ''[[A Touch of the Sun (1979 film)|A Touch of the Sun]]''\n| Jim Coburn\n|\n|-\n| ''[[A Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square (film)|A Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square]]''\n| Morgan Stanfield\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1980\n| ''[[The Ninth Configuration]]''\n| Sergeant in Comba