{"title_page": "2010 Linda McMahon U.S. Senate campaign", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox U.S. federal election campaign\n | committee        = Linda McMahon for Senate 2010\n | logo             = [[File:Linda2010banner.png|200px]]\n | campaign         = [[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2010|U.S. Senator from Connecticut]]\n | candidate        = [[Linda McMahon]]\n | cand_id          =\n | fec_date         =\n | status           = Lost\n | affiliation      = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]\n | headquarters     = [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]], [[Connecticut]]\n | key_people       = Ed Patru <small>(spokesman)</small>\n | receipts         = 50,285,122<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/races/summary.php?id=CTS2&cycle=2010|title=Connecticut Senate 2010 Race|author1=The Center for Responsive Politics |website=OpenSecrets}}</ref>\n | slogan           = A businesswoman, not a politician, for Connecticut\n | homepage         =\n}}\n\n[[Linda McMahon]], formerly CEO of [[World Wrestling Entertainment]], ran for '''[[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2010|U.S. Senator from Connecticut]]''' from September 16, 2009, to November 4, 2010. On May 21, 2010, she won a majority of support from the [[Connecticut Republican Party]]. She ran as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], promising lower taxes, [[fiscal conservatism]], and [[job creation]]. McMahon spent $50 million of her own money on the [[political campaign|campaign]], allowing her to refuse campaign donations from special interest groups.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2010/08/15/linda_mcmahon/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Linda McMahon | first=Dante | last=Ramos | date=August 15, 2010}}</ref>  She gained name recognition and popularity over her Republican opponents, including [[Rob Simmons]], the prior frontrunner.\n\nSimmons, who forced an August [[primary election]], had suspended his campaign shortly after the State Republican convention, but resumed campaigning in late July, participating in debates, and advertising on television.<ref name=SimmonsReturns>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/07/28/washington-wire-qa-rob-simmons|title=Washington Wire Q&A: Rob Simmons|last=Davis|first=Susan|publisher=The Wall Street Journal (blog)|date=July 28, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2010}}</ref> [[Peter Schiff]] gained placement on the primary ballot by collecting signatures. McMahon won the August 10 primary, but lost the general election to [[Richard Blumenthal]], then [[Attorney General of Connecticut]], her [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent.\n\n==Background==\nIn August 2009, McMahon's spokesperson said that she had considered running as a Republican candidate in the Connecticut Senate race for the seat then held by Democrat [[Christopher Dodd]]. McMahon announced her candidacy on the morning of September 16, 2009. Her husband assumed her duties as CEO at WWE effective immediately. Wrestling fans and political observers initially were incredulous, some thinking the announcement was an \"[[kayfabe|on-screen publicity stunt]]\". As McMahon began airing television and radio advertisements touting her business credentials, it became clear that the campaign was a serious effort.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2009/09/taking-linda-mcmahon-seriously.html|title= Linda McMahon's Company: News Desk|date=September 16, 2009|accessdate=2010-01-01|publisher=New Yorker online News Desk|author=Avi Zenilman}}</ref>\n[[Image:Rob Simmons 109th pictorial photo.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Before McMahon entered the Senate race, Rob Simmons was the Republican frontrunner]]\nMcMahon began her campaign encouraged by news of slumping approval ratings for Dodd. Her Republican opponents had directly attacked him, leveraging popular sentiment against his \"insider status\" and \"fiscal irresponsibility\". Connecticut voters stated that the economy and healthcare were their most pressing issues.<ref name=\"Quinnipiac poll-Nov\"/> A November poll showed Rob Simmons as the favorite in the Republican field with a 30\u201340-point lead over other candidates.<ref name=\"Quinnipiac poll-Nov\">{{cite web|url= http://www.quinnipiac.edu/x1296.xml?ReleaseID=1395|title= Simmons Runs Better Than McMahon Against Dodd, Quinnipiac University Poll Finds|accessdate= 2010-01-02|publisher= Quinnipiac University|location= Hamden, Connecticut|date= November 12, 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20091227125206/http://www.quinnipiac.edu/x1296.xml?ReleaseID=1395|archive-date= December 27, 2009|url-status= dead|df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign for the nomination==\n\n===2009===\n[[Image:LindaMcMahon web ad.jpg|thumb|170px|Linda McMahon ran a media campaign, launching statewide ads on radio, newspapers, mailing brochures, and Web ads targeting Connecticut voters]]\nMcMahon opened her campaign with a media blitz. She  advertised on television across the state.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Melissa |url=http://newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/holder-winfield_out-tweets_mcmahon/id_27700 |title=Holder-Winfield Out-Tweets McMahon |publisher=New Haven Independent |date=July 14, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon also hired high-profile campaign staff. Her campaign spokesman, Ed Patru, had worked on [[John McCain 2000 presidential campaign|John McCain's 2000 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"The Times (London)\">Whittell, Giles. \"$50 million says I'll wrestle my way to the Senate.\" The Times (London). March 18, 2010, Thursday NEWS; Pg. 29</ref> Her campaign manager, former State Senator David Cappiello, received a salary of roughly $280,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20091019/NWS12/310199943|title=MCMAHON HIRES EX-CONGRESSIONAL CANDIDATE|website=The Day}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=news-000003269112|title= McMahon Drops Fabulous Moolah on Manager|author= Toeplitz, Shira|publisher= CQ Politics|date= December 19, 2009|accessdate= 2010-01-25}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nMcMahon ran as an outsider, criticizing the Senate for its connection to [[Wall Street]] and [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008|federal banking bailouts]]. Her campaign ads emphasized her distance from politics, stressing she was \"not a career politician\". She criticized the current Senate for passing large bills in a perfunctory manner, particularly the [[Economic Stimulus Act of 2008|$800 billion stimulus package]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linda2010.com/blog_37.html|title= Common Sense we can all agree to...|date=October 2, 2009|accessdate=2009-10-19}}{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref> Her first televised political ad, \"Perseverance\", touted her experience as a business leader, stating, \"Thirty years ago, my husband and I started our business. It wasn't always easy but we grew it into a publicly traded company that's creating jobs here in Connecticut today.\"<ref>{{cite web|title= Linda McMahon's Campaign Ad Mentions 'Company,' Leaves Off Part About WWE|url= http://backporch.fanhouse.com/2009/09/24/linda-mcmahons-campaign-ad-mentions-company-leaves-off-part/|author= Ryan Wilson|date= September 24, 2009|accessdate= 2009-10-11|publisher=Fanhouse.com Sports News and Rumors}}</ref>\n\n====YouTube incident====\nIn October 2009, Democratic [[political operative]]s used [[YouTube]] videos of WWE for political ads. On October 16, Colleen Flanagan, a spokeswoman for Chris Dodd, posted controversial videos that showed the unsavory side of WWE on [[Talking Points Memo]], a political news website. She said the programming showed \"simulated rape, public sex and necrophilia\" and McMahon should not be Senator because she \"condones this type of behavior\". Hours later, YouTube removed the videos after contact from WWE. WWE had informed YouTube that the material was copyright under US law.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/news/ctpolitics/hc-mcmahon-wrestling-videos-1017.artoct17,0,4833759.story|title=Controversial Wrestling Videos Taken Down; Democrats Had Blasted Content|author=Christopher Keating|date=October 17, 2009|newspaper=The Hartford Courant|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Connecticut Democratic Party filed a complaint with the [[Federal Election Commission]] asking for an investigation into what happened with the controversial videos.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thrush |first=Glenn |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/glennthrush/1109/Dems_file_McMahonWWE_complaint.html# |title=Dems file McMahon-WWE complaint \u2013 Glenn Thrush |publisher=Politico.Com |date=November 2, 2009 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> The complaint claimed that of the \"almost 500,000\" videos of WWE on YouTube, the three were removed selectively to help McMahon's campaign.\n\n====Republican outsider====\n[[Image:Sam S.F. Caligiuri.jpg|thumb|120px|left|[[Sam Caligiuri]] dropped out of the U.S. Senate race in November 2009, leaving an intense rivalry between Simmons and McMahon]]\nIn October 2009, McMahon was viewed as a political outsider in the Republican Party (GOP). She faced competition from [[Sam Caligiuri]] and Rob Simmons, both established politicians among Connecticut Republicans. She lost some credibility among Republicans because of revelations about her voting record<ref group=\"nb\">\nMcMahon admitted to not voting in 2006 and in the 2008 Republican primaries, saying she decided not to after it became clear that [[John McCain]] was the presumptive Presidential nominee.\n\nBecause of faulty record-keeping at the Republican Registrar of voters in Greenwich, it was originally thought that she had only voted in 2000 and 2008. The claim\u2014which had been published in the Associated Press\u2014was debunked in January 2010 when the Registrar of votes in Greenwich admitted it had poor records, and had recently conducted a new search query. According to its investigation, McMahon had voted in the 2000, 2002, 2004, 2008, and 2009 elections.\n\n*See: [http://www.kocosports.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=30192&z=80 \" McMahon Acknowledges Spotty Voting Record.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713164024/http://www.kocosports.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=30192&z=80 |date=July 13, 2011 }} ''Congress Daily''. p. 20. Retrieved 2010-01-25. See: Summers, April. (September 23, 2009)\n*See: Haigh, Susan. (2009-09-23) \"Ex-wrestling CEO running for Senate missed voting.\" Associated Press Online. Retrieved 2010-01-25.\n*See {{cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/news/opinion/editorials/hc-rennie0927.artsep27,0,3918669.column |title=Five Hats Thrown into Republican Ring |work=Hartford Courant |date=September 27, 2009 |accessdate=2010-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930065911/http://www.courant.com/news/opinion/editorials/hc-rennie0927.artsep27,0,3918669.column |archive-date=September 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}\n*See: (2010-01-19) Neil, Vigdor. \"All eyes on McMahon's voting record in Greenwich.\" ''Connecticut Post''. Retrieved 2010-01-23.\n*See: Linda McMahon: \"I didn't vote, I regret it, I apologize, and I don't make any excuses for it\" KocoSports. Retrieved 2010-03-28.\n</ref> and past donations to Democrats, prompting speculation that she would run as an Independent candidate should she lose the Republican Primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20091011/OP05/310119998 |title=McMahon wrestles with her Senate run strategy |work=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/re.aspx?re=b2f91eae-4b13-4784-87d4-b69d7a688af0 |title=&#124; New London and southeastern Connecticut |work=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref>\n<ref>Keene, Tom (host) (taped 2009-12-01) \"Linda McMahon interview\". Bloomberg Surveillance with Tom Keene. Bloomberg Radio. Retrieved 2010-01-25.</ref>\n\nAs CEO of World Wrestling Entertainment, McMahon donated to Republicans and [[Democratic Leadership Council#Positions|Democratic Leadership Council]]-affiliated Democrats,<ref name=\"Political contribution history\">{{cite web|url=http://newsmeat.com/fec/bystate_detail.php?st=CT&last=McMahon&first=Linda|title=McMahon, Linda; Campaign Donor Search Machine|accessdate=2009-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714174535/http://newsmeat.com/fec/bystate_detail.php?st=CT&last=McMahon&first=Linda|archive-date=July 14, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=democrat>{{cite web|last=Beckel|first=Michael|title=Linda McMahon, a Republican, has strong ties to Democrats|publisher=[[OpenSecrets.org]]|date=September 16, 2009|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2009/09/wwe-chief-executive-linda-mcma.html|accessdate=2009-09-16}}</ref> including Sen. [[Joe Lieberman]] in 2006<ref name=lieberman>{{cite web|url=http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/diary/5073/|title=Hypocrite Joe taking $$$ from Pro Wrestling|last=Hamlin|first=Matt|publisher=My Left Nutmeg|date=December 26, 2006|accessdate=2009-08-21|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129164812/http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/diary/5073/|archive-date=January 29, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Rahm Emanuel]] from the period of 2002 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenextright.com/category/states/connecticut|author=Ironman (pseudonym)|title=Throwing her Chair into the Ring?|date=August 14, 2009|accessdate=2009-08-21|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120914004553/http://www.thenextright.com/category/states/connecticut|archive-date=September 14, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> McMahon donated $10,000 to the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]] on September 26, 2006, a contribution that helped [[Joe Courtney (politician)|Joe Courtney]] weeks before his win against Rob Simmons for the Second Congressional District.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/diary/11784/|title=Linda McMahon Helped Defeat Rob Simmons in 2006|author=tparty (blogger)|publisher=My Left Nutmeg blogs|date=September 17, 2009|accessdate=2010-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714143205/http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/diary/11784/|archive-date=July 14, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2009/09/wwe-chief-executive-linda-mcma.html Open Secrets online database, \"Linda McMahon\"'']</ref> Since 1980, McMahon contributed twice as much to Republicans as to Democrats\u2014($70,700 to Republicans, $35,100 to Democrats, and $1,000 to independents).<ref name=\"Simmons criticizes donations\"/> McMahon also donated to the [[Republican Majority for Choice]] in 2006,<ref name=\"Political contribution history\"/> a [[political action committee]] favoring [[abortion]] and the \"[[big tent]]\" political strategy of the GOP.  This record led conservative activists to label McMahon a [[RINO]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenextright.com/ironman/latest-wwe-character-linda-mcmahon-aka-the-wild-rino |title=Latest WWE character: Linda McMahon a/k/a \"the Wild RINO\" |publisher=The Next Right |accessdate=2010-02-07 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130205050532/http://www.thenextright.com/ironman/latest-wwe-character-linda-mcmahon-aka-the-wild-rino |archive-date=February 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n[[Image:Barack Obama and Rahm Emanuel in the Oval Office.jpg|thumb|210px|right|McMahon made several political donations to [[Rahm Emanuel]], Barack Obama's chief-of-staff, between 2002 and 2008]]\n\nConnecticut Republican voters were displeased to learn of McMahon's donations to Emanuel, a highly partisan figure who helped orchestrate the Democratic shift in the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] in 2006<ref name=\"Simmons criticizes donations\">{{cite web|title= GOP's Simmons, Caligiuri Criticize Linda McMahon For Donating More Than $35,000 To Democratic Candidates|author= Christopher Keating|date= October 11, 2009|accessdate= 2009-10-11|url= http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2009/10/gops-simmons-caligiuri-critici.html#more|publisher= The Courant|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100516051352/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2009/10/gops-simmons-caligiuri-critici.html#more|archive-date= May 16, 2010|url-status= dead|df= mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|presidential win]].<ref name=\"new yorker Emanuel\">{{cite magazine|title= The Gatekeeper: Rahm Emanuel on the job|author= Ryan Lizza|url= http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2009/03/02/090302fa_fact_lizza?currentPage=4|magazine=The New Yorker|date= 2009-03-02|accessdate= 2009-10-11}}</ref> McMahon explained to voters that her donations to Emanuel were on behalf of Rahm's brother, [[Ari Emanuel]], who had represented WWE in [[Hollywood]] since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |last=Stuart |first=Christine |url=http://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/election_2010/senate_candidate_talks_about_p.php |title=Senate Candidate Talks About Past ContributionsOpponents React |publisher=CT News Junkie |date=October 9, 2009 |accessdate=2010-02-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213071005/http://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/election_2010/senate_candidate_talks_about_p.php |archivedate=December 13, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>Tinley, James. (March 26, 2010) [http://www.nhregister.com/articles/2010/03/26/news/milford/doc4bacd909d0d10771049552.txt \"Milford Republicans courted by McMahon in Senate quest (video)\"] ''New Haven Register''. Retrieved 2010-03-27.</ref> According to McMahon, in 2002, \"He (Ari) called me one day and he said, my brother is running for Congress in Illinois. It happened to be Rahm. I didn't know Rahm.\" McMahon made more donations over the course of the next several years, including one check she wrote when Rahm Emanuel came to WWE headquarters to meet her.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ABSFY9Pn-2M&feature=player_embedded |title=Linda McMahon Discusses Donations To Rahm Emanuel And Liberal Democrats |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon's spokesperson clarified that McMahon didn't know who Rahm Emanuel was in '02, but was aware of his partisan status in '06.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shufflebarger |first=Jamie |url=http://hotlineoncall.nationaljournal.com/archives/2010/03/emanuel_becomes.php |title=Emanuel Becomes An Issue in CT GOP Race \u2013 Hotline on Call |work=National Journal |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100404060013/http://hotlineoncall.nationaljournal.com/archives/2010/03/emanuel_becomes.php |archive-date=April 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Wrestling in the spotlight====\n[[Image:Superstar Billy Graham.jpg|thumb|140px|right|Billy Graham, a former wrestler, was an outspoken critic of McMahon's campaign]]\nIn November 2009, former wrestler [[Superstar Billy Graham]] became an outspoken critic of McMahon's campaign. He said the McMahons were hypocrites for \"toning down\" the violence and sexuality in pro wrestling after many years of showing adult themes.<ref name=\"political smackdown\">{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/news/ctpolitics/hc-mcmahon-opposition-1118.artnov18,0,3727835.story|title= Political Smackdown: Former Wrestler Takes On McMahon|date= November 18, 2009|author=Christopher Keating|newspaper=The Hartford Courant|accessdate= 2010-02-07}}</ref> He launched Internet videos on WrestleView saying the WWE's switch to PG was politically motivated: \"...they (Linda and Vince) are doing it strictly to get Linda McMahon elected to Senator of Connecticut\", he stated in one video.<ref>{{cite web|title=Superstar Billy Graham Talks WWE's PG Rating |url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/interviews/video/superstar-billy-graham-talks-wwes-pg-rating-94161 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107013424/http://www.wrestlezone.com/interviews/video/superstar-billy-graham-talks-wwes-pg-rating-94161 |archivedate=January 7, 2010 }}</ref> Billy Graham contracted [[Hepatitis C]] from another wrestler's blood during his time in WWE and required a life-saving liver transplant as a result.<ref name=\"political smackdown\"/> When speaking about Linda, he said, \"She may look like a Sunday school teacher. Linda McMahon's hands are as bloody as her husband's because she is aware of every move in the ring. She has had no problem with grown men\u2014myself included\u2014cutting their head with a razor blade. All of a sudden, why aren't these guys bleeding anymore? Because Linda is running for the Senate.\" Graham told reporters that he was furious about having no pension and no health care after his wrestling career with WWE.<ref name=\"political smackdown\"/>\n\nMcMahon's campaign responded directly to Graham's accusations, saying he was a \"self-confessed liar\". On November 12, The campaign sent a letter directly to WrestleView, where Billy Graham had posted videos, attacking his credibility.<ref>Paglino, Nick. (November 12, 2009)[http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/article/exclusive-wwe-responds-to-billy-grahams-pg-allegations-90263 WWE responds to Billy Graham's PG-allegations] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109045534/http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/article/exclusive-wwe-responds-to-billy-grahams-pg-allegations-90263 |date=January 9, 2010 }} WrestleZone.com. Retrieved 2010-03-31.</ref> The campaign circulated an apology letter<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cdn.springboard.gorillanation.com/storage/wrestlezone.com/upl_images/pdf/BGrahamLetter.pdf|title=Graham apology}}</ref> Graham had written to the company in 1996, saying \"he has a habit of making false statements when he's not on WWE's payroll\". In the letter, Graham had admitted to making unjustified verbal attacks following his termination in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/70969-mcmahons-rise-puts-wrestlings-dangerous-history-in-the-spotlight|title=Linda McMahon's rise puts wrestling's dangerous history in the spotlight|date=December 7, 2009}}</ref><ref>Bix. (November 25, 2009) [http://www.cagesideseats.com/2009/11/25/1173840/linda-mcmahon-for-senator-roundup Linda McMahon for Senate Roundup] CageSideSeats Blog. Retrieved 2010-03-31.</ref>  Graham later reached out to apologize to McMahon for his comments, even offering to be a representative for her campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2011-03-31/news/billy-graham-made-it-big-in-wrestling-now-the-steroids-that-got-him-there-may-be-killing-him/4/ |title=Superstar Billy Graham Made It Big in Wrestling \u2013 Now the Steroids That Got Him There May Be Killing Him |date=March 31, 2011 |last=Pratt |first=Gregory |page=5 |work=[[Phoenix New Times]] |accessdate=May 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====McMahon-Simmons rivalry====\nMcMahon and Simmons engaged in negative campaigning in November 2009.<ref name=\"upcomingdebates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/Game-on-McMahon-Simmons-and-Schiff-gear-up-for-339135.php|title=Game on: McMahon, Simmons and Schiff gear up for debate|author=Neil Vigdor|work=Connecticut Post |date=January 27, 2010|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref><ref name=\"eugene\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/02/linda-mcmahon-fights-back-euge.html?icid=sphere_tribune_hartfordcourant_inline|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119174455/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/02/linda-mcmahon-fights-back-euge.html?icid=sphere_tribune_hartfordcourant_inline|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 19, 2013|title=Linda McMahon fights back: Eugene was \"inspirational\"|author=Daniela Altimari|date=February 5, 2010|publisher=The Hartford Courant Blogs|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> In one political mailing, McMahon portrayed Simmons to the [[Tea Party movement]] as a fraud.<ref>Klein, Rick. (February 1, 2010) [http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2010/02/rob-simmons-and-the-power-of-tea-bags----top-line-candidate-corner.html Rob Simmons and the Power of Tea Bags \u2013 \u2018Top Line\u2019 Candidate Corner]</ref>  (Simmons had courted Tea Party conservatives, and even carried a tea bag in his pocket<ref>[http://vodpod.com/watch/2337358-gop-senate-candidate-rob-simmons-boasts-of-adding-a-tea-bag-to-the-constitution during the campaign trail] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110002725/http://vodpod.com/watch/2337358-gop-senate-candidate-rob-simmons-boasts-of-adding-a-tea-bag-to-the-constitution |date=January 10, 2010 }}</ref>)<ref>{{cite web|author=Lee Fang |url=http://thinkprogress.org/2009/10/14/simmons-tea-bag/ |title=GOP Senate Candidate Rob Simmons Boasts of Adding A Tea Bag to the Constitution |website=Think Progress |date=October 14, 2009 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> In December, a [[Washington Times]] article suggested that Simmons' appeals to conservatives were insincere,<ref>Carpenter, Amanda. (December 9, 2009) [http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/dec/09/hot-button-19487319/?page=2 'Tea Party' poser?] Washington Times. Accessed 2010-03-26 Linda McMahon Press Release. Greenwich Blog of Record. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref> pointing to his past support for \"[[Emissions trading|cap and trade]]\" and \"[[card check]]\", two [[hot button issue]]s for the Tea Party.<ref>Patru, Ed. (December 10, 2009) [http://greenwichroundup.blogspot.com/2009/12/121009-greenwich-resident-linda-mcmahon.html Greenwich resident Linda McMahon is gaining momentum]</ref> McMahon's campaign savaged this apparent flip-flop, sending mailings to Connecticut voters highlighting the issue. This hurt Simmons' standing among conservatives and labor unions.<ref>Vigdor, Neil. (March 24, 2010)[http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/default/article/Simmons-conservative-credentials-called-into-421404.php#page-1 Simmons' conservative credentials called into question by union bosses] Stamford Advocate. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref>\n\n[[Image:Eugene.jpg|thumb|160px|right|Rob Simmons circulated YouTube videos of Eugene, a mentally challenged wrestler, in his negative campaigning against McMahon]]\n\nSimmons focused later advertising on criticizing McMahon and the WWE.<ref>[http://joinrobsimmons.com/accountability McMahon WWE Accountability Clock] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100508011838/http://joinrobsimmons.com/accountability |date=May 8, 2010 }}</ref> Many times, Simmons accused McMahon of trying to \"buy the election\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-01-01/news/hc-mcmahon-money-0101.artjan01_1_republican-senate-candidate-linda-mcmahon-well-heeled-partisans|title=Rob Simmons Says Linda McMahon Is Using Donations To Try To Buy Support}}</ref> In January, he circulated YouTube videos of wrestler [[Eugene (wrestler)|Eugene]] being humiliated on-screen, claiming the WWE was insensitive to the mentally challenged. The McMahon campaign countered, saying Eugene, rather than being ridiculed, was an inspirational character who ultimately became \"a hero\".\n\nSimmons launched negative ads attacking WWE's history of [[steroid abuse]],<ref>Rob Simmons for U.S. Senate (March 4, 2010) [https://web.archive.org/web/20120320060610/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/Letter%20to%20McMahon%20from%20Simmons_030410.pdf 10 Questions for Linda McMahon]</ref> its record of [[List of premature professional wrestling deaths|premature wrestler deaths]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_40140.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - WWE News: Linda McMahon's Senate opponent circulating video on high number of deceased wrestlers from WrestleMania 7 PPV (w/VIDEO)|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref> and circulated some of WWE's most [[political correctness|politically incorrect]] segments.<ref name=\"eugene\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T9oQFX0qHz0 |title= WWE Sandman beats the hell out of Eugene|author=DavidDH1996 (YouTube User)|date=December 17, 2008|publisher= YouTube.com|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref><ref>Lockhart, Brian. (February 12, 2010) [http://blog.ctnews.com/politicalcapitol/2010/02/12/norwalk-mayor-moccia-wants-mcmahon-simmons-to-turn-down-the-heat/ Norwalk Mayor Moccia wants McMahon, Simmons to turn down the heat] CT News. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref> By March 2010, the Simmons campaign had gone so negative that some established Connecticut Republicans began to denounce his attacks.<ref>Lockhart, Brian. 2010-02-21.[http://www.newstimes.com/news/article/Simmons-camp-has-concerns-about-GOP-chairman-374686.php#page-1 Simmons camp has 'concerns' about GOP chairman Healy]. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref><ref>Wright, Chase. (March 26, 2010)[http://www.thehour.com/story/484062 Moccia endorses McMahon for U.S. Senate] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717010056/http://www.thehour.com/story/484062 |date=July 17, 2011 }} The Hour Online. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref>\n\n===2010===\n\n====Blumenthal replaces Dodd====\n\nOn January 7, just hours after Chris Dodd announced his retirement, the [[Democratic State Central Committee of Connecticut|Connecticut Democratic Party]] launched [[Richard Blumenthal]], the Attorney General, as its new candidate.<ref name=\"dem press conference\">{{cite web|title= Richard Blumenthal for Senate Press Conference|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q7N-IrqptEU|author= CTBlogger (YouTube user)|accessdate= 2010-01-08|publisher=YouTube.com}}</ref> Blumenthal, who had a job approval rating over 80%, enjoyed near-unanimous support from Democrats and was considered a formidable opponent for any statewide office.<ref>Applebome, Peter. (January 6, 2010) [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/07/nyregion/07towns.html Smackdown for the Senate Takes a Twist] New York Times. Retrieved 2010-03-27.</ref>\n\nAlthough Connecticut is considered a solid Democratic-voting state, McMahon and Simmons sought to capitalize on the anti-establishment and anti-Democratic tide that had become a factor in the 2010 campaign season.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/01/connecticut-republicans-bask-i.html|title= Connecticut Republicans bask in glow of Scott Brown's win|author= Daniela Altimari|newspaper= Hartford Courant|date= January 19, 2010|accessdate= 2010-01-23|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://archive.today/20120707220922/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/01/connecticut-republicans-bask-i.html|archivedate= July 7, 2012|df= mdy-all}}</ref> In particular, [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]]'s [[United States Senate special election in Massachusetts, 2010|win in Massachusetts]] was seen as a good [[omen]] for Republicans nationally, as it showed that a Republican could win in a \"deep blue\" state.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b63HP13Lrkc|title= Linda McMahon on The View|publisher= YouTube|date= January 21, 2010|accessdate= 2010-01-23}}</ref> A key factor in Brown's win had been his demand for fiscal responsibility, which McMahon made her centerpiece issue, attacking Simmons for his voting record as U.S. Representative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linda2010.com/press-releases/2010/01/youre-no-scott-brown/ |title=You're No Scott Brown |publisher=Linda For Senate press releases |date=January 20, 2010 |accessdate=2010-02-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001140446/http://www.linda2010.com/press-releases/2010/01/youre-no-scott-brown/ |archivedate=October 1, 2010 }}</ref> In new mailings, she pointed to Simmons' D-rating from the [[National Taxpayers Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://blog.ctnews.com/politicalcapitol/2010/01/20/mcmahon-simmons-bicker-over-whos-more-like-scott-brown/#comments|title = McMahon, Simmons bicker over who's Scott Brown-ier|author= Brian Lockhart|date= January 20, 2010|accessdate= 2010-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, while Blumenthal continued to lead all Republican contenders by 20\u201330 points, McMahon took frontrunner status from Simmons.<ref>Pazniokas, Mark. (March 19, 2010) [http://ctmirror.com/story/5215/mcmahons-investment-produces-its-first-returns McMahon's Investment produces its first Returns] [[CT Mirror]]. Retrieved 2010-03-25.</ref><ref>Schwartz, Douglas. [http://www.quinnipiac.edu/x1296.xml?ReleaseID=1433 McMahon Wrestles To The Top In GOP Senate Race, Quinnipiac University Connecticut Poll Finds; Blumenthal Hammers Her 2-1] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322195015/http://www.quinnipiac.edu/x1296.xml?ReleaseID=1433 |date=March 22, 2010 }} Quinnipiac University. Published March 17, 2010. Retrieved March 25, 2010.</ref> Her rise in the polls was attributed largely to her heavy media presence, as a polling researcher pointed out, \"You can't miss her television ads. They're everywhere. She's the only candidate for Senate that's on TV right now.\"<ref name=\"march10pointlead\">Vigdor, Neil. (March 18, 2010) [http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/default/article/McMahon-overtakes-Simmons-in-latest-GOP-Senate-411714.php#page-1 McMahon overtakes Simmons in latest GOP Senate Poll] Stamford Advocate. Retrieved 2010-03-25.</ref> Political research showed that McMahon had gained strong popularity with female voters,<ref>Altimari, Daniela. (March 18, 2010) [http://articles.courant.com/2010-03-18/news/hc-capitol-watch-link-gop-poll-0317_1_linda-mcmahon-world-wrestling-entertainment-ceo-republican-women Linda McMahon has GOP Women in her Corner] Hartford Courant Blogs. Retrieved 2010-03-25.</ref> social conservatives,<ref>Altimari, Daniela. [http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/03/for-social-conservatives-the-m.html For Social Conservatives, \"the math points to Linda McMahon\"] {{webarchive|url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120926211749/http%3A//blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/03/for%2Dsocial%2Dconservatives%2Dthe%2Dm.html |date=September 26, 2012 }} Hartford Courant Blogs. Published March 25, 2010. Retrieved March 25, 2010.</ref> and residents in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]].<ref name=\"march10pointlead\"/>\n\n====April controversies====\nIn articles published by the ''New London Day'' and ''[[Politico.com]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100410/NWS12/304109913|title=McMahon warned doctor of probe|website=The Day}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/stories/0410/35599.html|title=Memo: McMahon tipped steroid doctor|first=Glenn|last=Thrush|website=POLITICO}}</ref> McMahon's controversial \"tip-off\" memo resurfaced, raising new questions regarding her ethical judgment. The 1989 memo asked a WWE executive to \"clue in\" a company doctor to possible legal action he might face from the Federal government.<ref name=\"1989memo\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/assets/pdf/NL7163449.PDF|title=McMahon's 1989 Memo}}</ref> At the time, the FBI was investigating the doctor for selling steroids to WWF wrestlers, including [[Vince McMahon]].\n\nThe timing of her memo was suspicious, as the investigation did not become public knowledge until May 27, 1990, the day of the doctor's arrest. When the articles were published, Linda did not respond, but WWE did, telling reporters that McMahon only wanted the doctor \"clued in\" so he would know why he was fired.<ref name=\"Lindasrole\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-mcmahon_memo_0410.artapr10,0,2139987.story|title=Memo raises questions about role in 1989 case}}</ref> WWE said McMahon learned of the investigation through a company lawyer who had heard the Federal prosecutor involved, James West, carelessly talking about the case at a fundraising event.<ref name=\"Lindasrole\"/> West said the WWE's story was a lie,<ref name=\"wwe-west explanation\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100411/NWS12/304119975|title=Ex-prosecutor says McMahon camp wrong on WWF warning|website=The Day}}</ref> denying ever discussing the case or attending the event in question.<ref name=\"wwe-west explanation\"/><ref name=\"wwe-west explanation\"/><ref>Sex, Lies, and Headlocks. p. 92</ref> Although West and WWE continued to point fingers, McMahon and her campaign did not publicly discuss the story and its ongoing controversy. The news hurt McMahon's public image<ref>{{cite news |author=Anonymous |url=http://www.norwichbulletin.com/Opinion/x57953354/Our-view-McMahon-owes-state-an-explanation |title=Our view: McMahon owes state an explanation \u2013 Norwich, CT |newspaper=Norwich Bulletin |date=April 16, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120907035617/http://www.norwichbulletin.com/Opinion/x57953354/Our-view-McMahon-owes-state-an-explanation |archivedate=September 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and, according to her critics, it provided evidence she had tried to \"undermine a criminal investigation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100412/NWS12/100419955|title=Simmons goes on the attack|website=The Day}}</ref>\n\nAn article published in the ''[[Stamford Advocate]]'' raised attention to McMahon's voter registration drive at the [[University of Connecticut]], where college students were to be paid a $5 bonus for each voter they registered as a Republican.<ref name=\"$5votes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Paying-for-voters-McMahon-campaign-plan-draws-460248.php#page-1|title= Paying for voters: McMahon campaign plan draws questions|author=Brian Lockhart|newspaper=Stamford Advocate|date=April 23, 2010}}</ref> The potential [[moral hazard]] in such a program created negative associations to [[Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now|ACORN]]'s [[Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now#2008: Presidential campaign|2008 controversy]] regarding invalid voter applications. Although the practice was not illegal,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/local/article/Paying-for-voters-McMahon-campaign-plan-draws-460927.php |title=Paying for voters? McMahon campaign plan draws questions \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=April 24, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> the bonus structure was removed from the drive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailycampus.com/news/mcmahon-under-fire-for-voter-bounties-1.1434516|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719141324/http://www.dailycampus.com/news/mcmahon-under-fire-for-voter-bounties-1.1434516|url-status=dead|title=McMahon under fire for voter 'bounties'|archivedate=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-04-27/news/hc-ct-mcmahon-voters-0427.artapr27_1_linda-mcmahon-voter-registration-voter-fraud|title=Linda McMahon Withdraws Bonus Offer For Voter Registration}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com/2010/04/mcmahon-campaign-cancels-money-for-gop-registrations-voter-drive.php?ref=mp|title=McMahon Campaign Cancels Money-For-GOP Registrations Voter Drive &#124; Talking Points Memo|date=April 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====''The New York Times'' Vietnam story====\n{{Main|Richard Blumenthal#New York Times Vietnam story}}\n[[Image:Richard Blumenthal  speaking with Scott Slifka.jpg|thumb|230px|right|[[Richard Blumenthal]], left, was the Democratic nominee for the U.S. Senate. During her campaign, McMahon capitalized on faulty statements he made about his Vietnam service]]\nMcMahon focused her attention towards the presumptive Democratic challenger in the few weeks before the convention. On May 12, she launched political TV ads on Blumenthal's apparent [[flip-flop (politics)|flip-flop]] on [[Political Action Committee|PAC contributions]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/news/local/statewire/hc-ap-ct-connsenatemay12,0,783402.story |title=McMahon ad targets Blumenthal in Conn. Senate race |access-date=June 3, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515140653/http://www.courant.com/news/local/statewire/hc-ap-ct-connsenatemay12,0,783402.story |archive-date=May 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On May 17, a story in ''[[The New York Times]]'' revealed that Blumenthal had [[Richard Blumenthal#Controversy surrounding statements of service in Vietnam|made false claims]] about his military service during the [[War in Vietnam]].\n\nOn May 19, McMahon said that she played a role in ''The New York Times'' story<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyructions.com/mcmahon-strikes-turns-blumenthal-into-bruce-caputo/|title=McMahon Strikes. Turns Blumenthal into Bruce Caputo.}}</ref> and confirmed that her campaign helped uncover the facts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/news/breaking/hc-mcmahon-admits-campaign-role-times-blumenthal,0,7678442.story|title=McMahon Confirms Campaign's Role In N.Y. Times Story On Blumenthal}}</ref> Her campaign sent a video of Blumenthal's questionable speech to the newspaper. Days later, McMahon's campaign posted a full version of that speech on YouTube, which showed Blumenthal clearly explaining his \"Vietnam era\" service early in his speech, clearing the discrepancy.<ref name=\"McMahon softens blow\">{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/right-now/2010/05/linda_mcmahon_campaign_acciden.html |title=Right Now \u2013 Linda McMahon campaign accidentally softens the blow of Blumenthal story |publisher=Voices.washingtonpost.com |date=May 19, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> The full version was a godsend for the Blumenthal campaign, and it softened the blow dealt by his later \"in Vietnam\" gaffe.<ref name=\"McMahon softens blow\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100520/NWS12/305209466|title=Video mitigates Blumenthal remarks|website=The Day}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/05/blumenthal-and-vietnam-the-dir.html|archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20111113071932/http%3A//blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/05/blumenthal%2Dand%2Dvietnam%2Dthe%2Ddir.html|url-status=dead|title=Blumenthal and Vietnam, the Director's cut|archivedate=November 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-blumenthal-folo-0520-20100520-story.html|title=Blumenthal Counters With Longer Version Of Video|first=By DANIELA|last=ALTIMARI|website=courant.com}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon's campaign spokesman, Ed Patru, later told reporters that the campaign strategically \"put its fingerprints\" on the story to impress Republican delegates before the convention.<ref name=\"the smackdown candidate\"/>\n\n====Republican convention====\nMcMahon, Schiff, and Simmons competed for the nomination at the convention on May 21, 2010.<ref name=\"RepConvention\">Jacobs, Jeremy P. (2010\u201301) Politics (Campaigns & Elections). Reds and Blues: State Spotlight \u2013 Connecticut. January 2010 issue, Vol. 31, Issue 1, p51</ref><ref>[http://www.newstimes.com/local/article/In-the-face-of-doubters-Simmons-Senate-campaign-470114.php In the face of doubters, Simmons' Senate campaign projecting optimism in buildup to GOP convention]</ref> Prior to the Convention, McMahon had urged supporters to register for the Republican primary, suggesting that she would run even if she had not won the Republican nomination.<ref name=\"LindaStrategy\"/> Schiff similarly had indicated that he would run regardless of the convention's results.<ref>{{cite web |last=Toeplitz |first=Shira |url=http://blogs.cqpolitics.com/eyeon2010/2010/03/schiff-hits-the-air-without-th.html |title=Schiff Hits The Air \u2013 Without The (R) \u2013 The Eye (CQ Politics) |publisher=Blogs.cqpolitics.com |date=March 29, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331110751/http://blogs.cqpolitics.com/eyeon2010/2010/03/schiff-hits-the-air-without-th.html |archivedate=March 31, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nSimmons, the ostensible Party favorite, staked his campaign on the convention and said repeatedly he would not \"force a primary\" if he lost the convention.<ref name=\"LindaStrategy\">{{cite web|url=http://ctlocalpolitics.net//2010/02/01/mcmahons-strategy-has-simmons-camp-on-ropes/|title= McMahon's Strategy Has Simmons' Camp on Ropes|author=Vincent (blogger)|date=February 1, 2010|publisher=Connecticut Local politics|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> However, when Simmons lost many of his pledged delegates to McMahon, his viability was doubted by the media and state GOP.<ref>[http://cookpolitical.com/node/3343 Connecticut Senate: Can McMahon Topple Blumenthal?] Cook Political Report. April 29, 2010.</ref><ref name=\"simmonsprojects\"/><ref>[http://blog.joinrobsimmons.com/14-days-til-convention-and-the-momentum-is-growing/ Rob Simmons \u2013 14 days til convention and the momentum is growing!]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Pundits revealed that Simmons was under pressure to drop out and run for [[Connecticut's 2nd congressional district|his former Congressional seat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtnh.com/dpp/news/connecticut/ct%27s-senate%2C-attorney-general-campaigns|title=CT's Senate, Attorney General campaigns|publisher=WTNH.com Channel 8 News|date=January 12, 2010|accessdate=2010-02-09}}</ref> When Simmons was asked about the possibility,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/video/top-line-tea-partys-candidate-connecticut-9719867|title=Video: Tea Party's Candidate in Connecticut|website=ABC News}}</ref> he did not explicitly \"rule out\" a change in races.<ref name=\"Simmonsruleout\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2010/02/simmons-wont-rule-out-run-for-former-house-seat.html|title= Simmons Won't Rule Out Run for Former House Seat|publisher=The Note : ABC News|author=Rick Klein|date= February 1, 2010|accessdate=2010-02-09}}</ref> Simmons was visibly frustrated by the negative media publicity he received as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100207/NWS12/302079934/1018|title=Simmons brings new perspectives to Senate race|author=Ted Mann|publisher=The Day|date=February 7, 2010|accessdate=2010-02-09}}</ref> Simmons then claimed that he had more delegates than McMahon by a wide margin.<ref name=\"simmonsprojects\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newstimes.com/local/article/In-the-face-of-doubters-Simmons-Senate-campaign-470114.php|title=In the face of doubters, Simmons' Senate campaign projecting optimism in buildup to GOP convention|author=Neil Vigdor|date=April 30, 2010}}</ref> McMahon heavily outspent Simmons, maintaining a steady lead over both her rivals. Simmons could not fund TV ads after a drop in fundraising.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0110/32212.html|title=Simmons' 4Q fundraising drops off|author=Josh Kraushaar|publisher=Politico.com|date=January 29, 2010|accessdate= 2010-02-09}}</ref> In the weeks prior to the convention, Simmons failed to regain in the polls.<ref name=\"simmons and 1992\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100425/OP04/304259942|title=Simmons versus the checkbook|author=Paul Choiniere|publisher=The Day|date=April 25, 2010|accessdate=2010-01-25}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = State Republican Convention results (first round)<ref name=\"politico1\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = '''Linda McMahon'''*\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = '''737'''\n| percentage = '''51.76'''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Rob Simmons*\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 632\n| percentage = 44.62\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Peter Schiff\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 44\n| percentage = 3.11\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Vincent Forras\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 7\n| percentage = 0.49\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Ethan Book\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 0\n| percentage = 0.00\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 1,414\n| percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n<small>* Denotes candidate met the minimum threshold of 15 percent to appear on the primary ballot</small>\n\n<small>* 708 delegates were required to win endorsement from the Republican Party</small><ref name=\"the smackdown candidate\">{{cite magazine|last=Rice |first=Andrew |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/10_24/b4182066684319.htm |title=The Smackdown Candidate |magazine=BusinessWeek |date=June 3, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n\nSchiff was polling at roughly 10% days before the convention and told many of his pledged delegates at the convention to switch to Simmons \"because I didn't think McMahon was playing fair.\" Schiff told his supporters that McMahon's campaign had about 40 members on the convention floor attempting to garner more support while votes were being cast, breaking convention rules.<ref name=conventionupdate>{{cite video\n | people      = Peter Schiff\n | date        = May 22, 2010\n | title       = Schiff for Senate \u2013 Republican convention results\n | url         = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=koiXvCzvGlw\n | format      = Video blog\n | medium      = Flash\n | publisher   = Schiff Report\n | location    = [[Stamford, Connecticut]]\n | accessdate  = 2010-05-23\n}}</ref>\n\nSimmons was deeply disappointed to lose on the first round of voting.<ref name=\"simmons politico interview\"/> Despite his promise to the contrary, Simmons then decided to force a primary with McMahon.<ref name=\"politico1\">{{cite web|author=Andy Barr | url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0510/37633.html | title=McMahon wins GOP nod in Conn. \u2013 Shira Toeplitz and Maggie Haberman |publisher=Politico.Com |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Four days later, on May 25, Simmons reversed himself again, and suspended his campaign, saying he could not compete financially with McMahon's deep pockets.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/26/nyregion/26simmons.html | work=The New York Times | title=Simmons Suspends Campaign for Connecticut Senate | first=Raymond | last=Hernandez | date=May 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ctmirror1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6241/gop-defies-history-primaries |title=Republican hopefuls no longer deferring to convention delegates' decision &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=June 1, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604072032/http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6241/gop-defies-history-primaries |archivedate=June 4, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Simmons-ends-campaign-but-stays-on-ballot-499060.php#page-2 |title=Simmons: Grudging retreat, but no surrender \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=May 25, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Although Simmons was no longer campaigning, he often disparaged McMahon to the press. He told [[The National Review]] that he did not think McMahon \"can win at all\". He also said that if she were to ask for his help, he would say he was \"preoccupied\".<ref>Costa, Robert. (May 26, 2010) [http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ODkxZmFlMmM4OTRkNTUwMjgwYzYzM2EwODkxNjc0ZjY Hard Feelings in Hartford] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527220917/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ODkxZmFlMmM4OTRkNTUwMjgwYzYzM2EwODkxNjc0ZjY |date=May 27, 2010 }}</ref> Simmons said he did McMahon a favor by stopping his campaign, but he did not endorse her.<ref name=\"simmons politico interview\"/> He said he would not call off the August primary because \"voters deserve another choice.\"<ref name=\"simmons politico interview\">{{cite web |last=Toeplitz |first=Shira |url=http://dyn.politico.com/printstory.cfm?uuid=D711A3F5-18FE-70B2-A8A50E72F3709E4F |title=Simmons 'sorry' for ripping McMahon \u2013 POLITICO.com Print View |publisher=Dyn.politico.com |date=May 26, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100731035311/http://dyn.politico.com/printstory.cfm?uuid=D711A3F5-18FE-70B2-A8A50E72F3709E4F |archive-date=July 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Many of Simmons' hardcore backers also refused to back McMahon.<ref name=\"theday1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100528/NWS01/305289957/-1/NWS |title=Peter Schiff tackling McMahon momentum &#124; News from southeastern Connecticut |publisher=The Day |date=May 28, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref name=\"theday1\"/>\n\nIn late July, Simmons re-entered the race by airing ads on TV reminding Republican primary goers that he was still on the ballot, as well as by participating in debates and editorial board discussions.<ref name=SimmonsReturns/>\n\n====Republican primary====\n[[Image:SchiffSpeaking.png|thumb|left|140px|Peter Schiff, who failed to gain 15% of Republican support at the Republican Convention, collected petitions to challenge her in an August Primary]]\nIn the weeks after her victory at the Republican Convention, McMahon fared poorly in political polls<ref name=\"25 points behind\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100603/INTERACT010403/100609881 |title=Linda McMahon: Jury's still out on steroid risks &#124; News from southeastern Connecticut |publisher=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McClarin |first=Jim |url=http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/06/the-week-from-heck-for-linda-m.html |title=The Week From Heck For Linda McMahon \u2013 Rick Green &#124; CT Confidential |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707065029/http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/06/the-week-from-heck-for-linda-m.html |archivedate=July 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and suffered from high unfavorability ratings among both Democrats and Republicans.<ref>{{cite web |last=Snyder |first=Mike |url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/05/q-poll-blumenthal-trumps-mcmah.html |title=Q Poll: Blumenthal trumps McMahon by 25 points; voters shrug off Vietnam matter \u2013 Capitol Watch |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120930043930/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/05/q-poll-blumenthal-trumps-mcmah.html |archivedate=September 30, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Cook Political Report]] attributed much of the damage in her public image to months of criticism from Simmons and the media.<ref name=\"june cook political\">{{cite web|url=http://cookpolitical.com/node/3343 |title=2010 Senate \u2013 CT &#124; The Cook Political Report |publisher=Cookpolitical.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article7144836.ece|title=timesonline.co.uk|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=June 6, 2010}}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> On June 8, McMahon released her own [[political polling|internal polling]] to assure Republicans she was competitive with Blumenthal.<ref name=\"polling with a twist\">http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6366/spin-twist-mcmahon-says-her-polling-close-blumenthals Spin with a twist: McMahon says her polling is close to Blumenthal's</ref>\n\nNonetheless, negative sentiment towards McMahon fueled some momentum for both Simmons and Schiff.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/political-landscape-murky-elections-connecticut-hawaii/story?id=10729055 |title=Political Landscape Gets Murky After Elections in Connecticut, Hawaii \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Some Republican voters who had supported Simmons turned to Schiff, who shared their resentment towards McMahon and the convention.<ref>{{cite web|last=Miller |first=Sean J. |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/101243-blumenthal-more-popular-in-wake-of-media-storm |title=Blumenthal more popular in wake of media storm \u2013 The Hill's Ballot Box |publisher=Thehill.com |date= June 3, 2010|accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Hazlett |first=Bob |url=http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/06/schiff-neck-and-neck-with-mcm.html |title=Peter Schiff on Linda McMahon: 'I Will Be the Frontrunner.' \u2013 Rick Green &#124; CT Confidential |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120708111010/http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/06/schiff-neck-and-neck-with-mcm.html |archivedate=July 8, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rasmussenreports.com/public_content/politics/elections/election_2010/election_2010_senate_elections/connecticut/toplines/toplines_connecticut_senate_june_1_2010|title=Toplines - Connecticut Senate - June 1, 2010 - Rasmussen Reports\u00ae|website=www.rasmussenreports.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Katz |first=Marisa |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/postpartisan/2010/05/twisting_the_truth_in_the_conn.html |title=PostPartisan \u2013 Twisting the truth in the Connecticut Senate race |publisher=Voices.washingtonpost.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Schiff fared poorly in the convention, but collected over 10,000 signatures from Connecticut residents was placing him on the primary ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Schiff-enlists-paid-consulting-firm-to-help-507943.php |title=Schiff enlists paid consulting firm to help collect signatures \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=June 1, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Schiff-lives-to-fight-another-day-against-McMahon-532070.php |title=Schiff lives to fight another day against McMahon \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=June 21, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Mothersopposingmcmahon.jpeg|thumb|right|Mothers Opposing McMahon, a [[527 group]], was established in July 2010]]\nMcMahon spent the remainder of June and July attempting to control the wrestling element of her public image, which repeatedly received negative media attention.<ref>{{cite news|last=Condon |first=Stephanie |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20008911-503544.html |title=Linda McMahon Airs Ad Featuring WWE History \u2013 Political Hotsheet |publisher=CBS News |date=June 25, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> On June 22, McMahon's campaign gained unwanted attention\n<ref>{{cite web |author=WrestlingNewsWorld.com |url=http://www.wrestlingnewsworld.com/wwe-news/linda-mcmahon-trends-yahoo-in-lieu-of-lawsuit.php |title=Linda McMahon Trends Yahoo in Lieu of Lawsuit |publisher=Wrestlingnewsworld.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718122346/http://www.wrestlingnewsworld.com/wwe-news/linda-mcmahon-trends-yahoo-in-lieu-of-lawsuit.php |archive-date=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> from a lawsuit filed by [[Martha Hart]], the wife of deceased wrestler [[Owen Hart]], in regard to a wrestling DVD featuring her husband.<ref name=\"martha hart sues\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6527/mcmahon-being-sued-widow-former-wrestler |title=McMahon being sued by widow of former wrestler &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=June 22, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> The WWE said her lawsuit was \"meritless\", nothing more than a \"political hit job.\"<ref name=\"martha hart sues\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/sports/slapped+with+lawsuit+from+Canadian+wrestler+Owen+Hart+widow/3192093/story.html |title=WWE slapped with lawsuit from Canadian wrestler Owen Hart's widow |publisher=Vancouversun.com |date=June 23, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727221943/http://www.vancouversun.com/sports/slapped%2Bwith%2Blawsuit%2Bfrom%2BCanadian%2Bwrestler%2BOwen%2BHart%2Bwidow/3192093/story.html |archivedate=July 27, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amlawdaily.typepad.com/amlawdaily/2010/06/wwe-widow-suit.html |title=Nixon Peabody, K&L Gates Spar Over Wrestling Widow's Suit Against WWE and Senate Candidate |publisher=Amlawdaily.typepad.com |date=June 23, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.journalinquirer.com/articles/2010/06/23/politics_and_government/doc4c220ab77bc25756023144.txt|title=McMahon camp, WWE: Lawsuit is contract issue, political stunt|first=Susan HaighAssociated|last=Press|website=Journal Inquirer}}</ref> McMahon launched TV ads embracing her career in WWE, downplaying negative opinion of wrestling as a form of \"soap opera\" entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hVsM8hb-21TZfsamXPJ254_0w9JQD9GHSPO80|title=McMahon: Wrestling was soap opera|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628054936/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hVsM8hb-21TZfsamXPJ254_0w9JQD9GHSPO80|archivedate=June 28, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Davis |first=Susan |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/06/25/linda-mcmahon-talks-wwe-in-campaign-ad/ |title=Linda McMahon Talks WWE in Campaign Ad \u2013 Washington Wire \u2013 WSJ |publisher=Blogs.wsj.com |date=June 25, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Becker |first=Bernie |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/25/mcmahon-mentions-wrestling-in-new-ad/ |title=McMahon Mentions Wrestling in New Ad - The Caucus Blog - NYTimes.com |publisher=Thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com |date=June 25, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6554/mcmahons-new-ad-features-wrestling-call-shake-things |title=McMahon's new ad embraces controversial wrestling role &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=June 24, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703151008/http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6554/mcmahons-new-ad-features-wrestling-call-shake-things |archivedate=July 3, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In July 2010, five women from West Hartford attacked her wrestling career, saying WWE encouraged profane and violent treatment of women.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/14/linda-mcmahon-ct-senate-c_n_646347.html |title=Linda McMahon, CT Senate Candidate, Slammed By Mothers Group Over WWE Past (VIDEO) |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= July 14, 2010|accessdate=2010-08-14 |first=Jason |last=Linkins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.wnct.com/news/2010/jul/13/conn-moms-oppose-mcmahon-over-wrestling-ties-ar-298693/|title=Conn. Moms Oppose Mcmahon Over Wrestling Ties|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716190741/http://www2.wnct.com/news/2010/jul/13/conn-moms-oppose-mcmahon-over-wrestling-ties-ar-298693/|archive-date=July 16, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> The McMahon campaign dismissed their group, Mothers Opposing McMahon, as a group of [[political operative|Democratic operatives]], arguing that their press conference was organized and paid for by the [[Connecticut Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/07/15/mothers-group-slams-mcmahon-role-wwe-ceo/ |title=Dem Mothers' Group Slams McMahon Over Former Role as WWE CEO |publisher=FOXNews.com |date=April 7, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Nonetheless, McMahon's campaign continued to fend off attacks, such as the [[Linda McMahon#Tom Cole|Tom Cole affair]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Ben |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/bensmith/0710/McMahon_and_the_ring_boy.html |title=McMahon and the 'ring boy' \u2013 Ben Smith |publisher=Politico.Com |date=July 31, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> and when she pretended to kick [[Jim Ross]] before firing him as part of a WWE storyline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/08/06/wrestling-ceo-vince-mcmah_n_673703.html |title=Wrestling CEO Vince McMahon Sick of Wife Linda McMahon's Senate Smackdown |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=August 8, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n\n=====Primary results=====\nMcMahon won the Republican nomination on August 10 with 49% of the vote. Her win received a great deal of national attention, plenty of media coverage, and congratulatory calls from national Republicans [[Mitt Romney]] and [[John Cornyn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/McMahon-basks-in-congratulations-national-612600.php |title=McMahon basks in congratulations, national attention \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date= August 12, 2010|accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon also received calls from Schiff and Simmons offering their support.<ref name=\"mcmahon win\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100812/NWS12/308129474/1080/nws |title=Democrats deride McMahon win &#124; News from southeastern Connecticut |publisher=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon's lack of a majority was derided by critics as a sign that Republicans were not fully satisfied with her candidacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100812/OP01/308129493 |title=Low turnout sets stage for big election &#124; News from southeastern Connecticut |publisher=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Simmons said it was possible that Schiff was a spoiler in the campaign, [[vote splitting|siphoning off support]] that could have helped him defeat McMahon.<ref name=\"mcmahon win\"/>\n\n==General election==\nDuring the general election, McMahon campaigned in small towns and appeared with local Republicans, positioning herself as a [[populism|populist]] candidate against \"establishment\" figure Blumenthal.\n\n===Lance Cade's death===\n{{Wikinews|US professional wrestler Lance Cade dies aged 29}}\nThe death at age 29 from heart failure of former WWE wrestler, [[Lance Cade]], in August 2010 renewed controversy over WWE.<ref name=\"death renews focus\">\"http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/Wrestler-s-death-renews-focus-on-McMahon-WWE-619584.php</ref> Cade had abused painkillers and steroids during his career in WWE. When a reporter asked her about Cade, McMahon replied the WWE had no more ability to prevent his death \"than a studio could have prevented [[Heath Ledger]]'s death\".<ref name=\"the hill\"/> She also told the Connecticut Post \"I may have met him once\".<ref name=\"death renews focus\"/> Cade's father disputed McMahon's assertion of so distant a connection,<ref name=\"father blasts McMahon\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100826/nws12/308269378|title=Dead wrestler's father blasts McMahon, WWE|website=The Day}}</ref> and her remarks prompted former WWE wrestler [[Christopher Nowinski]] to speak out against McMahon and the WWE.<ref name=\"nowinski interview\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/08/former-wrestler-mcmahon-kicking-dirt-on-the-grave-of-lance-cade/61782/ | title=Former Wrestler: McMahon 'Kicking Dirt on the Grave' of Lance Cade| date=August 19, 2010}}</ref> He alleged that the abuse of steroids and painkillers was encouraged and rewarded by the company, saying McMahon was \"just kicking dirt on the guy's grave.\"<ref name=\"nowinski interview\"/> He also related a conversation he'd had with Cade in which Cade expressed a desire to stop using steroids, but said, \"the pressure is to use them, because the WWE rewards the guys who use them.\"<ref name=\"death renews focus\"/><ref name=\"the hill\">{{Cite web | url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/114957-ex-wrestler-wwe-rewards-steroid-use-says-mcmahon-knew- |title = Wrestler's death puts spotlight on McMahon's WWE ties|date = August 19, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"nowinski interview\"/><ref name=\"wwe hits back\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/08/wwe-hits-back-at-nowinski/61851/|title=WWE Hits Back at Nowinski|date=August 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWWE quickly responded to Nowinski's accusations, saying, \"It is very dubious that he ever had a conversation with Lance Cade much less Lance Cade confiding to a total stranger that he used painkillers and steroids.\"<ref name=\"wwe hits back\"/> The company also sought to discredit Nowinski by claiming that he had failed to disclose that he'd suffered previous concussions before signing his contract with WWE, as was required.<ref name=\"wwe hits back\"/> They further disputed his claims as to the number of days wrestlers worked, on average, and observed that despite Nowinski's renown in the area of [[Chronic traumatic encephalopathy|CTE]], a form of brain injury resulting from repeated concussions, he is not an expert in matters relating to steroids or pain killers.<ref name=\"wwe hits back\"/> The charge that Nowinski was a \"stranger\" to Cade was refuted by Nowinski: He and Lance Cade had been tag team partners during 2002\u20132003, and co-workers until 2007.<ref name=\"the hill\"/>\n\n===Attacks on Blumenthal's credibility===\n{{quote|I've never taken PAC money, and I have rejected all special interest money because I have stood strong and taken legal action against many of those special interests|[[Richard Blumenthal]]|}}\n\nIn August 2010, McMahon damaged Blumenthal's credibility by publicizing an apparent [[flip-flop (politics)|flip-flop]] he made on PAC donations. She used both TV ads and mailers to portray him as \"dishonest\" for accepting over $480,000 in PAC money in 2010,<ref>http://www.ctmirror.org/story/7387/mcmahon-steps-attacks-blumenthalK{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> following $17,000 during the 1980s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hotair.com/archives/ed-morrissey/2010/08/23/blumenthal-took-pac-money-despite-claims-to-have-refused-it/|title=Blumenthal took PAC money despite claims to have refused it|date=August 23, 2010|website=Hot Air}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/08/mcmahon-chronicles-ii.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-08-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707071651/http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/08/mcmahon-chronicles-ii.html |archivedate=July 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\nIn October, McMahon aired TV ads comparing Blumenthal to departing Senator Chris Dodd and the corruption of the [[Countrywide financial political loan scandal|Countrywide scandal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://townhall.com/tipsheet/guybenson/2010/10/21/finally-mcmahon-ties-blumenthal-to-chris-dodd-in-connecticut-n715488|title=Finally: McMahon Ties Blumenthal to Chris Dodd in Connecticut|first=Guy|last=Benson|website=Townhall}}</ref><ref name=\"theatlanticwire.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/opinions/view/opinion/In-Connecticut-Race-McMahon-Spends-Blumenthal-Soars-5490|title=In Connecticut Race, McMahon Spends, Blumenthal Soars - The Atlantic|date=October 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Blumenthal-McMahon-trade-charges-in-second-debate-691441.php|title=Blumenthal, McMahon trade charges in second debate|first1=Ken|last1=Dixon|first2=Staff|last2=Writer|date=October 8, 2010|website=Connecticut Post}}</ref> During a debate on October 7, McMahon criticized his vote as a state Senator in 1989 for a $850 million tax increase. Blumenthal fired back, referencing her memo to Pat Patterson, saying that while he was a state Senator in 1989, \"she was tipping off the doctor who worked for her about a federal investigation, a criminal investigation.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Blumenthal-McMahon-trade-charges-in-2nd-debate-691441.php | title=Blumenthal, McMahon trade charges in second debate| date=October 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Scott Brown endorsement===\nOn October 9, Linda McMahon received the endorsement of Massachusetts U.S. Senator [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20101010/NWS01/310109815/-1/NWS |title=Scott Brown campaigns for McMahon |last=Mann |first=Ted |publisher=The Day (Connecticut) |date=October 10, 2010 |accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref> a Republican who had been elected to the Senate in a [[United States Senate special election in Massachusetts, 2010|January 2010 special election]] to the seat long-held by Democrat [[Ted Kennedy]]. The rally was held in front of [[Milford, Connecticut|Milford]] City Hall and was attended by around 250 people. Brown had also faced a once-favored Democratic state attorney general in his bid for U.S. Senate, [[Martha Coakley]].\n\n==Political positions==\nMcMahon campaigned on a platform of [[fiscal conservatism]], lower taxes, and job creation.<ref name=\"first100days\">{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/news/opinion/hc-mcmahon-senator-100-days.artfeb28,0,952366,print.story|title=Linda McMahon: My first 100 days|newspaper=Hartford Courant|author=Linda McMahon|date=February 28, 2010|accessdate=2010-03-09}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She opposed the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|2009 stimulus act]], saying the money from the stimulus \"went into government agencies, not the hands of small businesses that are going to create 70% of jobs.\"<ref name=\"Courant interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/news/ctpolitics/hc-mcmahon-retrospect-1220.artdec20,0,985577,full.story |title=Linda McMahon Wrestling in New Ring: Politics |author=Daniela Altimari |publisher=Hartford Courant |date=2009-12-20 |accessdate=2010-01-17 |work=The Hartford Courant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928023022/http://www.courant.com/news/ctpolitics/hc-mcmahon-retrospect-1220.artdec20%2C0%2C985577%2Cfull.story |archivedate=September 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> McMahon also denounced [[deficit spending]], expressing support for a [[Balanced budget amendment|Constitutional balanced budget amendment]].<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linda2010.com/images/pdf/Linda_McMahon_Jobs_Plan.pdf |title=Jobs Plan PDF |accessdate=2010-06-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021210851/http://www.linda2010.com/images/pdf/Linda_McMahon_Jobs_Plan.pdf |archivedate=October 21, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linda2010.com/issues/fiscal-discipline/|title=Fiscal Discipline \u2013 Linda McMahon for Senate|accessdate=2010-03-08|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326134551/http://www.linda2010.com/issues/fiscal-discipline |archivedate=March 26, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> McMahon blamed [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democrats]] for not reclaiming unspent money from the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]] (TARP) and the bailout package, saying the money should be used to repay government debts.<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/><ref group=\"nb\">\nMcMahon gave an interview supporting TARP in its original form, which was to purchase toxic assets in the context of a financial crisis. Nevertheless, she has been a strong opponent of the TARP program throughout the campaign, saying that the government overstepped its authority in purchasing shares of the automobile and banking industries.\n*See [http://www.linda2010.com/news/2009/11/qa-linda-mcmahon-talks-west-hartford-politics/ West Hartford interview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227065343/http://www.linda2010.com/news/2009/11/qa-linda-mcmahon-talks-west-hartford-politics/ |date=December 27, 2010 }}\n*See [http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2009/12/mcmahon-ad-hands-simmons-a-con.html McMahon ad hands Simmons a conservative club, UPDATED] December 9, 2009</ref> She also accused the [[Executive Branch]] of evading the system of [[checks and balances]] through the use of \"[[czar (political term)#Criticism|policy czars]]\" and [[executive order (United States)|executive orders]].<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/>\n\nMcMahon attacked [[the Federal Reserve]] for \"[[micromanaging]]\" small banks through the stimulus programs and called for an end to bank bailouts.<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/> McMahon alleged that the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132010|U.S. financial crisis]] could be attributed in part to the repeal of the [[Glass\u2013Steagall Act]] in 1999, and advocated that Congress [[Glass\u2013Steagall Act#Proposed reenactment|revisit the issue]].<ref name=\"mcmahonlikesherchances\"/> She stated that small business creates most new jobs, and that government created many obstacles to economic recovery. She pushed for greater credit availability to help businesses invest.<ref name=\"mcmahonlikesherchances\"/>\n\nOn April 7, 2010, McMahon's campaign unveiled a jobs plan to \"put Connecticut back to work.\" The plan was modeled on [[Reaganomics]], crediting [[John Rutledge (economist)|Dr. John Rutledge]], who wrote many of Reagan's policies in 1980\u201381, as Chief Economic Adviser to the McMahon campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ameriborn.com/?p=2407 |title=Linda McMahon Releases Jobs Plan |publisher=Ameriborn.com |date=April 7, 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707130538/http://ameriborn.com/?p=2407 |archive-date=July 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Proposals in the plan included:\n<ref>{{cite web|author=Evan McMorris-Santoro |date= May 14, 2010<!--, 9:22&nbsp;am -->|url=http://tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com/2010/05/doh-linda-mcmahon-picks-now-to-call-for-more-offshore-drilling.php |title=D'oh! Linda McMahon Picks Now To Call For More Offshore Drilling &#124; TPMDC |publisher=Tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/05/14/linda-mcmahon-connecticut_n_576301.html |title=Linda McMahon, Connecticut Senate Contender: Now Is The Time To Promote Offshore Oil Drilling |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= May 14, 2010|accessdate=2010-08-14 |first=Jason |last=Linkins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jonathan Kantrowitz |url=http://blog.ctnews.com/kantrowitz/2010/05/15/linda-mcmahon-drill-baby-drill/ |title=Linda McMahon: Drill Baby, Drill \u2013 Jonathan Kantrowitz \u2013 Connecticut News |publisher=Blog.ctnews.com |date=May 15, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n* lower tax rates for [[capital gains tax in the United States|capital gains]] and [[dividend]]s\n* abolition of the [[estate tax]] and the [[gift tax in the United States|gift tax]]\n* greater tax deductions to encourage savings for [[Individual Retirement Account|IRAs]] and higher education\n* passage of pending free trade agreements with [[United States \u2013 Colombia Free Trade Agreement|Colombia]], [[Panama \u2013 United States Trade Promotion Agreement|Panama]], and [[South Korea \u2013 United States Free Trade Agreement|South Korea]]\n* government deregulation, rejecting [[cap and trade]] and [[card check]] legislation<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/>\n\nMcMahon supported [[offshore drilling]]. After the [[BP Oil Spill]], a McMahon spokesman said she desired stronger penalties for such incidents, but believed a moratorium on new drilling would devastate economies in [[Gulf of Mexico|Gulf]] states, and make America \"more dependent on foreign oil\".<ref name=\"drillingspeech\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtHAqY8n5Js&feature=player_embedded |title=McMahon Downplays \"Accidents\" Like BP Gulf Oil Spill, Argues for More Offshore Drilling |publisher=YouTube |date=May 24, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhregister.com/articles/2010/06/15/news/doc4c17c54a49dc6388223986.txt |title=Spill estimates grow; Blumenthal says rein in Big Oil- The New Haven Register \u2013 Serving New Haven, Connecticut |publisher=Nhregister.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> She supported expanded drilling, naming the [[Outer Continental Shelf]], [[ANWR]], the [[Green River Formation]], and the [[Bakken Formation|Bakken Shale Deposits]] as attractive sites for energy exploration.<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/> McMahon also supported alternative energy, including [[fuel cell|fuel-cell]], [[solar energy|solar]], [[wind energy|wind]] and [[geothermal energy|geothermal technology]].<ref name=\"mcmahonlikesherchances\">{{cite web |last=Benjamin |first=Scott |url=http://www.housatonictimes.com/articles/2010/04/23/news/political/doc4bd1a65533bee562586762.txt |title=McMahon Likes Her Chances \u2013 News |publisher=Housatonic Times |date=April 23, 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130125212157/http://www.housatonictimes.com/articles/2010/04/23/news/political/doc4bd1a65533bee562586762.txt |archivedate=January 25, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"drillingspeech\"/>\n\nMcMahon claimed to be socially moderate. She was [[pro-choice]], and donated to [[Republican Majority for Choice]]. She did not support [[partial birth abortions]] and favored [[parental notification]] laws.<ref name=\"Courant interview\"/> McMahon opposed amnesty for [[illegal immigrants]] and supported [[Mexico - United States border#Security|border security]]. She supported fixing the visa application process to encourage legal [[immigration]]. She generally supported [[gay rights]], including the repeal of [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell]]. She personally felt that marriage should be between a man and a woman, but favored [[states rights|state authority]] on the issue of [[same-sex marriage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b63HP13Lrkc |title=Linda McMahon on the View |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon voiced displeasure with federal statutes on same-sex marriage, such as the [[Defense of Marriage Act]].<ref name=\"first returns\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/5215/mcmahons-investment-produces-its-first-returns |title=McMahon's investment produces its first returns &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=March 19, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n\nOn [[United States foreign policy|foreign policy]], McMahon expressed interest in joining a defense-related [[United States congressional committee|committee in the Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/opinion/opedcolumnists/connecticut_is_ready_to_rumble_XC9xevF2Rr2t4HXkGThSiK#ixzz0wmiDXZWf|title=Connecticut is ready to rumble|author=Maureen Callahan|accessdate=2010-08-15 | work=New York Post | date=August 15, 2010}}</ref> Concerning the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]], McMahon said she was \"apprehensive about the economic repercussions of a protracted war\", but said \"It is my hope that we bring our troops home safely as soon as possible, but we should bring them home responsibly and in victory, not defeat.\"<ref name=\"Courant interview\"/> During a Republican debate, she took a \"hawkish\" stance on [[Iran]], saying all options should be on the table, including the military one.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstimes.com/news/article/GOP-Senate-candidates-spar-in-debate-388520.php |title=GOP Senate candidates spar in debate |publisher=NewsTimes |date=March 2, 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-03}}</ref> She said that the U.S. military should be \"second to none\", and promised more representation to [[defense contractors]] from Connecticut, including [[Sikorsky Aircraft|Sikorsky]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/08/16/connecticut-gop-candidates-seize-use-russian-choppers-afghanistan/ | work=Fox News | title=Connecticut GOP Candidates Seize on U.S. Use of Russian Choppers in Afghanistan | date=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Analysis==\n\n===Campaign scrutiny===\nThe McMahon campaign was criticized for providing only limited direct access to the candidate. McMahon was accompanied by political staff at all public events. She limited her press availability to scheduled one-on-one interviews, avoiding traditional press conferences and impromptu questions. Staff highly controlled her photo opportunities, Twitter postings, and public events, often not notifying the press of events in advance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Wrestling-s-steel-magnolia-McMahon-closes-in-on-607482.php |title=Wrestling's steel magnolia, McMahon closes in on GOP nod \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=August 7, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref name=\"press questioner\">{{cite web|last=Cole |first=Joseph |url=http://valley.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/linda_mcmahon_makes_her_case_in_seymour/ |title=Linda McMahon States Her Case in Seymour &#124; Valley Independent Sentinel |publisher=Valley.newhavenindependent.org |date=February 26, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bass |first=Paul |url=http://www.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/mcmahon_reality_checks_independent/ |title=McMahon \"Reality Checks\" Independent |publisher=New Haven Independent |date=March 2, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McClarin |first=Jim |url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/04/rob-simmons-linda-mcmahon-and.html |title=Rob Simmons, Linda McMahon and the Fourth Estate \u2013 Capitol Watch |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707013545/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/04/rob-simmons-linda-mcmahon-and.html |archivedate=July 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yourct.com/2010/03/linda-mcmahon/ |title=Linda McMahon |publisher=YourCT.com |date=March 6, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718143523/http://www.yourct.com/2010/03/linda-mcmahon/ |archive-date=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nMcMahon did not discuss the topic of federal programs such as [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], [[Medicaid]] and [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] in the weeks before the Republican primary, leading to accusations she was avoiding controversial issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/7074/mcmahon-promises-change-while-avoiding-controversy |title=McMahon promises change, avoids controversy on difficult issues &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=August 2, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812032258/http://www.ctmirror.org/story/7074/mcmahon-promises-change-while-avoiding-controversy |archivedate=August 12, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \"She claims she wants to cut federal spending, yet refuses to discuss her position on Medicare and Social Security, two of the most costly entitlement programs.\"<ref name=\"theatlanticwire.com\"/>\n\n===McMahon family campaign presence===\n[[Image:Mrmcmahon092407.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Vince McMahon did not appear on the campaign trail with Linda for much of her campaign.]]\nMcMahon's husband, Vince McMahon, did not actively campaign for his spouse, causing some to wonder if Linda was purposely distancing herself from him.<!-- who?--><ref>Vigdor, Neil. (March 26, 2010) [http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Paging-Vince-McMahon-Flamboyant-WWE-showman-424644.php#page-1 Paging Vince McMahon: Flamboyant WWE showman keeps a low profile during wife's Senate run ] Stamford Advocate. Retrieved 2010-03-29.</ref> In February 2010, Linda said Vince was too busy \"running the company\" as both chairman and [[CEO]] to campaign, but said he may be involved \"down the road\".<ref>Kate Snow, David Muir. ABC News Transcript. (January 9, 2010) \"Senate Smackdown: Former Female CEO Running for Office.\" Televised on ABC World News Saturday. Waterbury, Connecticut. Retrieved 2010-02-06.</ref> Several speculators predicted that if he campaigned with her, his direct association with controversial wrestling skits would be a \"major liability\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2009/09/will-wwe-chair-vince-mcmahon-hurt-lindas-senate-hopes/|title=Will WWE Chair Vince McMahon Hurt Linda's Senate Hopes?|first=Ben|last=Buchwalter}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon's son-in-law, WWE wrestler [[Triple H]], gave an interview<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VNFubVuFcJ4|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref> to ''The Wall Street Journal'' on March 12, 2010, where he said he had purposely kept an \"arms length away from Linda\" during her campaign to avoid giving her bad publicity. On March 14, 2010, a news story in the ''Stamford Advocate'' revealed that her husband, Vince McMahon, owned a 47-foot sports yacht called ''The Sexy Bitch''.<ref>[http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/The-running-of-the-rich-Is-wealth-changing-406355.php#page-1 The running of the rich: Is wealth changing Connecticut politics?]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/article/vince-mcmahon-earns-linda-mcmahon-some-bad-press-98123 |title=Wrestlezone article \u2013 Vince McMahon earns Linda McMahon some bad press |access-date=June 3, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322194906/http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/article/vince-mcmahon-earns-linda-mcmahon-some-bad-press-98123 |archive-date=March 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>Collins, David. (March 19, 2010) [http://www.theday.com/article/20100319/NWS05/303199849/-1/NWS Linda McMahon's yacht is named what?! '''The Day''' Accessed 2010-03-19.]</ref> Linda's absence from the wrestling industry was also noted on April 20, when an article by the ''[[Greenwich Time (newspaper)|Greenwich Time]]'' reported that she was courting voters in [[Westport, Connecticut]] while her husband was running a live wrestling event at the [[Mohegan Sun Arena]].<ref>[http://www.greenwichtime.com/local/article/Originally-in-Sunday-s-paper-SmackDown-comes-463405.php Originally in Sunday's paper: 'SmackDown' comes to Connecticut as Linda McMahon keeps a distance]</ref>\n\nVince McMahon appeared together with Linda for the first time on April 21, 2010, at a charity function at [[Sacred Heart University]]. At one point during the event, he reportedly grabbed a microphone and said to Richard Blumenthal:\n{{quote|My name is Vince McMahon and my wife is the one who's going to beat you this fall.<ref>{{cite web |last=McCrackin |first=Phil |url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/04/vince-mcmahon-to-dick-blumenth.html |title=Vince McMahon to Dick Blumenthal: My wife will whoop you \u2013 Capitol Watch |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120708043425/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/04/vince-mcmahon-to-dick-blumenth.html |archivedate=July 8, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= lordsofpain.net| url=http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/wwe/7526.html |accessdate=June 3, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501230047/http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/wwe/7526.html |archivedate=May 1, 2010 }}</ref>}}\n\n====Vince McMahon's activities====\nThrough October and November 2010, Vince McMahon took increasing action to support fans and the company image which he believed was being damaged by Linda's campaign. On several occasions, [[Connecticut Secretary of State]] [[Susan Bysiewicz]] stated that poll workers had the right to bar voters wearing WWE merchandise to the polls, claiming they were \"political items\". WWE filed a federal lawsuit against Bysiewicz to prevent this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/breaking-news/hc-xpm-2010-10-26-hc-vince-mcmahon-lawsuit-1026-story.html|title=A Defiant Vince McMahon Has Filed A Lawsuit Against Susan Bysiewicz|first=DANIELA|last=ALTIMARI|website=courant.com}}</ref> He also launched a \"Stand up for WWE\" campaign on the Internet and gave away company T-shirts and merchandise.\n\nOn October 30, 2010, WWE held a \"Fan Appreciation Day\" in Hartford, Connecticut. Vince acknowledged that the event was held to counter the negative publicity from the Senate race.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.newstimes.com/default/article/Democrats-file-elections-complaint-against-World-714956.php |title = Democrats accuse McMahon of improperly using WWE resources|date = October 21, 2010}}</ref> During the wrestling show, McMahon distanced himself from his wife's political campaign, saying, \"Some people may think I was going to talk about politics today. Nothing could be further from the truth. I do encourage you to vote this Tuesday, and while you're voting, feel free to wear a WWE T-shirt. I came out here to simply say thank you. That's what this day is all about. It's about fan appreciation. No one appreciates the fans more than World Wrestling Entertainment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20101030/NWS12/101039984|title=Wrestling for votes? Nope. Just wrestling|website=The Day}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2010-10-30-hc-gop-campaigning-1031-20101030-story.html|title=WWE Fans Urged To Vote|first=CHRISTOPHER|last=KEATING|website=courant.com}}</ref> The Connecticut Democratic Party filed an FEC complaint against Linda McMahon's campaign in October, claiming the WWE's \"Fan Appreciation Day\" was an \"illegal campaign contribution\". The complaint also cited the taping of \"Smackdown in Bridgeport Harbor Yard\" on [[Election Day (United States)|Election Day]], claiming it intended to suppress voter turnout in a Democratic-leaning community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/stories/1010/43899.html|title=Dems want FEC slam on McMahon|first=Jake|last=Sherman|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\n===2012 candidacy===\n\nMcMahon ran in the [[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2012]], and lost to [[Chris Murphy (Connecticut politician)|Chris Murphy]].\n\n==Results==\n{{Election box begin \n| title = United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statementofvote-sots.ct.gov/StatementOfVote/WebModules/ReportsLink/USSenTownView.aspx?Parameter=11/02/2010-General |title=Statement of Vote: Election Results for United States Senator Summarized by Town |publisher=The State of Connecticut Secretary of the State |accessdate=December 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101122180406/http://www.statementofvote-sots.ct.gov/StatementOfVote/WebModules/ReportsLink/USSenTownView.aspx?Parameter=11%2F02%2F2010-General |archivedate=November 22, 2010 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n| candidate = Richard Blumenthal\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 636,040\n| percentage = 55.16%\n| change = -11.20%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = Linda E. McMahon\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 498,341\n| percentage = 43.22%\n| change = +11.08%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = Warren B. Mosler\n| party = Independent (politician)\n| votes = 11,275\n| percentage = 0.98%\n| change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = Dr. John Mertens\n| party = Connecticut for Lieberman\n| votes = 6,735\n| percentage = 0.58%\n| change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = Write-in candidates (8)\n| party = Write-in candidate\n| votes = 724\n| percentage = 0.06%\n| change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  |votes      = 137,755\n  |percentage = 11.95%\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box total\n| votes = 1,153,115\n| percentage = 100\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no swing\n  |winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |loser = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2010]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart=126623 | fec=S0CT00151 | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Linda_McMahon.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/person/9269027 Appearances] on [[C-SPAN]] programs\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/linda_e_mcmahon/index.html Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/gIQAPjsz6O_topic.html Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* -->\n*[http://www.opensecrets.org/races/summary.php?cycle=2010&id=CTS2 Campaign contributions] at [[OpenSecrets.org]]\n\n{{United States elections, 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linda Mcmahon U.S. Senate Campaign, 2010}}\n[[Category:2010 United States Senate elections]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox U.S. federal election campaign\n | committee        = Linda McMahon for Senate 2010\n | logo             = [[File:Linda2010banner.png|200px]]\n | campaign         = [[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2010|U.S. Senator from Connecticut]]\n | candidate        = [[Linda McMahon]]\n | cand_id          =\n | fec_date         =\n | status           = Lost\n | affiliation      = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]\n | headquarters     = [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]], [[Connecticut]]\n | key_people       = Ed Patru <small>(spokesman)</small>\n | receipts         = 50,285,122<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/races/summary.php?id=CTS2&cycle=2010|title=Connecticut Senate 2010 Race|author1=The Center for Responsive Politics |website=OpenSecrets}}</ref>\n | slogan           = A businesswoman, not a politician, for Connecticut\n | homepage         =\n}}\n\n[[Linda McMahon]], formerly CEO of [[World Wrestling Entertainment]], ran for '''[[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2010|U.S. Senator from Connecticut]]''' from September 16, 2009, to November 4, 2010. On May 21, 2010, she won a majority of support from the [[Connecticut Republican Party]]. She ran as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], promising lower taxes, [[fiscal conservatism]], and [[job creation]]. McMahon spent $50 million of her own money on the [[political campaign|campaign]], allowing her to refuse campaign donations from special interest groups.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2010/08/15/linda_mcmahon/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Linda McMahon | first=Dante | last=Ramos | date=August 15, 2010}}</ref>  She gained name recognition and popularity over her Republican opponents, including [[Rob Simmons]], the prior frontrunner.\n\nSimmons, who forced an August [[primary election]], had suspended his campaign shortly after the State Republican convention, but resumed campaigning in late July, participating in debates, and advertising on television.<ref name=SimmonsReturns>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/07/28/washington-wire-qa-rob-simmons|title=Washington Wire Q&A: Rob Simmons|last=Davis|first=Susan|publisher=The Wall Street Journal (blog)|date=July 28, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2010}}</ref> [[Peter Schiff]] gained placement on the primary ballot by collecting signatures. McMahon won the August 10 primary, but lost the general election to [[Richard Blumenthal]], then [[Attorney General of Connecticut]], her [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent.\n\n==Background==\nIn August 2009, McMahon's spokesperson said that she had considered running as a Republican candidate in the Connecticut Senate race for the seat then held by Democrat [[Christopher Dodd]]. McMahon announced her candidacy on the morning of September 16, 2009. Her husband assumed her duties as CEO at WWE effective immediately. Wrestling fans and political observers initially were incredulous, some thinking the announcement was an \"[[kayfabe|on-screen publicity stunt]]\". As McMahon began airing television and radio advertisements touting her business credentials, it became clear that the campaign was a serious effort.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2009/09/taking-linda-mcmahon-seriously.html|title= Linda McMahon's Company: News Desk|date=September 16, 2009|accessdate=2010-01-01|publisher=New Yorker online News Desk|author=Avi Zenilman}}</ref>\n[[Image:Rob Simmons 109th pictorial photo.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Before McMahon entered the Senate race, Rob Simmons was the Republican frontrunner]]\nMcMahon began her campaign encouraged by news of slumping approval ratings for Dodd. Her Republican opponents had directly attacked him, leveraging popular sentiment against his \"insider status\" and \"fiscal irresponsibility\". Connecticut voters stated that the economy and healthcare were their most pressing issues.<ref name=\"Quinnipiac poll-Nov\"/> A November poll showed Rob Simmons as the favorite in the Republican field with a 30\u201340-point lead over other candidates.<ref name=\"Quinnipiac poll-Nov\">{{cite web|url= http://www.quinnipiac.edu/x1296.xml?ReleaseID=1395|title= Simmons Runs Better Than McMahon Against Dodd, Quinnipiac University Poll Finds|accessdate= 2010-01-02|publisher= Quinnipiac University|location= Hamden, Connecticut|date= November 12, 2009|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20091227125206/http://www.quinnipiac.edu/x1296.xml?ReleaseID=1395|archive-date= December 27, 2009|url-status= dead|df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign for the nomination==\n\n===2009===\n[[Image:LindaMcMahon web ad.jpg|thumb|170px|Linda McMahon ran a media campaign, launching statewide ads on radio, newspapers, mailing brochures, and Web ads targeting Connecticut voters]]\nMcMahon opened her campaign with a media blitz. She  advertised on television across the state.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Melissa |url=http://newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/holder-winfield_out-tweets_mcmahon/id_27700 |title=Holder-Winfield Out-Tweets McMahon |publisher=New Haven Independent |date=July 14, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon also hired high-profile campaign staff. Her campaign spokesman, Ed Patru, had worked on [[John McCain 2000 presidential campaign|John McCain's 2000 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"The Times (London)\">Whittell, Giles. \"$50 million says I'll wrestle my way to the Senate.\" The Times (London). March 18, 2010, Thursday NEWS; Pg. 29</ref> Her campaign manager, former State Senator David Cappiello, received a salary of roughly $280,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20091019/NWS12/310199943|title=MCMAHON HIRES EX-CONGRESSIONAL CANDIDATE|website=The Day}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=news-000003269112|title= McMahon Drops Fabulous Moolah on Manager|author= Toeplitz, Shira|publisher= CQ Politics|date= December 19, 2009|accessdate= 2010-01-25}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nMcMahon ran as an outsider, criticizing the Senate for its connection to [[Wall Street]] and [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008|federal banking bailouts]]. Her campaign ads emphasized her distance from politics, stressing she was \"not a career politician\". She criticized the current Senate for passing large bills in a perfunctory manner, particularly the [[Economic Stimulus Act of 2008|$800 billion stimulus package]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linda2010.com/blog_37.html|title= Common Sense we can all agree to...|date=October 2, 2009|accessdate=2009-10-19}}{{dead link|date=February 2012}}</ref> Her first televised political ad, \"Perseverance\", touted her experience as a business leader, stating, \"Thirty years ago, my husband and I started our business. It wasn't always easy but we grew it into a publicly traded company that's creating jobs here in Connecticut today.\"<ref>{{cite web|title= Linda McMahon's Campaign Ad Mentions 'Company,' Leaves Off Part About WWE|url= http://backporch.fanhouse.com/2009/09/24/linda-mcmahons-campaign-ad-mentions-company-leaves-off-part/|author= Ryan Wilson|date= September 24, 2009|accessdate= 2009-10-11|publisher=Fanhouse.com Sports News and Rumors}}</ref>\n\n====YouTube incident====\nIn October 2009, Democratic [[political operative]]s used [[YouTube]] videos of WWE for political ads. On October 16, Colleen Flanagan, a spokeswoman for Chris Dodd, posted controversial videos that showed the unsavory side of WWE on [[Talking Points Memo]], a political news website. She said the programming showed \"simulated rape, public sex and necrophilia\" and McMahon should not be Senator because she \"condones this type of behavior\". Hours later, YouTube removed the videos after contact from WWE. WWE had informed YouTube that the material was copyright under US law.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/news/ctpolitics/hc-mcmahon-wrestling-videos-1017.artoct17,0,4833759.story|title=Controversial Wrestling Videos Taken Down; Democrats Had Blasted Content|author=Christopher Keating|date=October 17, 2009|newspaper=The Hartford Courant|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Connecticut Democratic Party filed a complaint with the [[Federal Election Commission]] asking for an investigation into what happened with the controversial videos.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thrush |first=Glenn |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/glennthrush/1109/Dems_file_McMahonWWE_complaint.html# |title=Dems file McMahon-WWE complaint \u2013 Glenn Thrush |publisher=Politico.Com |date=November 2, 2009 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> The complaint claimed that of the \"almost 500,000\" videos of WWE on YouTube, the three were removed selectively to help McMahon's campaign.\n\n====Republican outsider====\n[[Image:Sam S.F. Caligiuri.jpg|thumb|120px|left|[[Sam Caligiuri]] dropped out of the U.S. Senate race in November 2009, leaving an intense rivalry between Simmons and McMahon]]\nIn October 2009, McMahon was viewed as a political outsider in the Republican Party (GOP). She faced competition from [[Sam Caligiuri]] and Rob Simmons, both established politicians among Connecticut Republicans. She lost some credibility among Republicans because of revelations about her voting record<ref group=\"nb\">\nMcMahon admitted to not voting in 2006 and in the 2008 Republican primaries, saying she decided not to after it became clear that [[John McCain]] was the presumptive Presidential nominee.\n\nBecause of faulty record-keeping at the Republican Registrar of voters in Greenwich, it was originally thought that she had only voted in 2000 and 2008. The claim\u2014which had been published in the Associated Press\u2014was debunked in January 2010 when the Registrar of votes in Greenwich admitted it had poor records, and had recently conducted a new search query. According to its investigation, McMahon had voted in the 2000, 2002, 2004, 2008, and 2009 elections.\n\n*See: [http://www.kocosports.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=30192&z=80 \" McMahon Acknowledges Spotty Voting Record.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713164024/http://www.kocosports.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=30192&z=80 |date=July 13, 2011 }} ''Congress Daily''. p. 20. Retrieved 2010-01-25. See: Summers, April. (September 23, 2009)\n*See: Haigh, Susan. (2009-09-23) \"Ex-wrestling CEO running for Senate missed voting.\" Associated Press Online. Retrieved 2010-01-25.\n*See {{cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/news/opinion/editorials/hc-rennie0927.artsep27,0,3918669.column |title=Five Hats Thrown into Republican Ring |work=Hartford Courant |date=September 27, 2009 |accessdate=2010-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930065911/http://www.courant.com/news/opinion/editorials/hc-rennie0927.artsep27,0,3918669.column |archive-date=September 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}\n*See: (2010-01-19) Neil, Vigdor. \"All eyes on McMahon's voting record in Greenwich.\" ''Connecticut Post''. Retrieved 2010-01-23.\n*See: Linda McMahon: \"I didn't vote, I regret it, I apologize, and I don't make any excuses for it\" KocoSports. Retrieved 2010-03-28.\n</ref> and past donations to Democrats, prompting speculation that she would run as an Independent candidate should she lose the Republican Primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20091011/OP05/310119998 |title=McMahon wrestles with her Senate run strategy |work=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/re.aspx?re=b2f91eae-4b13-4784-87d4-b69d7a688af0 |title=&#124; New London and southeastern Connecticut |work=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref>\n<ref>Keene, Tom (host) (taped 2009-12-01) \"Linda McMahon interview\". Bloomberg Surveillance with Tom Keene. Bloomberg Radio. Retrieved 2010-01-25.</ref>\n\nAs CEO of World Wrestling Entertainment, McMahon donated to Republicans and [[Democratic Leadership Council#Positions|Democratic Leadership Council]]-affiliated Democrats,<ref name=\"Political contribution history\">{{cite web|url=http://newsmeat.com/fec/bystate_detail.php?st=CT&last=McMahon&first=Linda|title=McMahon, Linda; Campaign Donor Search Machine|accessdate=2009-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714174535/http://newsmeat.com/fec/bystate_detail.php?st=CT&last=McMahon&first=Linda|archive-date=July 14, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=democrat>{{cite web|last=Beckel|first=Michael|title=Linda McMahon, a Republican, has strong ties to Democrats|publisher=[[OpenSecrets.org]]|date=September 16, 2009|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2009/09/wwe-chief-executive-linda-mcma.html|accessdate=2009-09-16}}</ref> including Sen. [[Joe Lieberman]] in 2006<ref name=lieberman>{{cite web|url=http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/diary/5073/|title=Hypocrite Joe taking $$$ from Pro Wrestling|last=Hamlin|first=Matt|publisher=My Left Nutmeg|date=December 26, 2006|accessdate=2009-08-21|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129164812/http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/diary/5073/|archive-date=January 29, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Rahm Emanuel]] from the period of 2002 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenextright.com/category/states/connecticut|author=Ironman (pseudonym)|title=Throwing her Chair into the Ring?|date=August 14, 2009|accessdate=2009-08-21|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120914004553/http://www.thenextright.com/category/states/connecticut|archive-date=September 14, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> McMahon donated $10,000 to the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]] on September 26, 2006, a contribution that helped [[Joe Courtney (politician)|Joe Courtney]] weeks before his win against Rob Simmons for the Second Congressional District.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/diary/11784/|title=Linda McMahon Helped Defeat Rob Simmons in 2006|author=tparty (blogger)|publisher=My Left Nutmeg blogs|date=September 17, 2009|accessdate=2010-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714143205/http://www.myleftnutmeg.com/diary/11784/|archive-date=July 14, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2009/09/wwe-chief-executive-linda-mcma.html Open Secrets online database, \"Linda McMahon\"'']</ref> Since 1980, McMahon contributed twice as much to Republicans as to Democrats\u2014($70,700 to Republicans, $35,100 to Democrats, and $1,000 to independents).<ref name=\"Simmons criticizes donations\"/> McMahon also donated to the [[Republican Majority for Choice]] in 2006,<ref name=\"Political contribution history\"/> a [[political action committee]] favoring [[abortion]] and the \"[[big tent]]\" political strategy of the GOP.  This record led conservative activists to label McMahon a [[RINO]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenextright.com/ironman/latest-wwe-character-linda-mcmahon-aka-the-wild-rino |title=Latest WWE character: Linda McMahon a/k/a \"the Wild RINO\" |publisher=The Next Right |accessdate=2010-02-07 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130205050532/http://www.thenextright.com/ironman/latest-wwe-character-linda-mcmahon-aka-the-wild-rino |archive-date=February 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n[[Image:Barack Obama and Rahm Emanuel in the Oval Office.jpg|thumb|210px|right|McMahon made several political donations to [[Rahm Emanuel]], Barack Obama's chief-of-staff, between 2002 and 2008]]\n\nConnecticut Republican voters were displeased to learn of McMahon's donations to Emanuel, a highly partisan figure who helped orchestrate the Democratic shift in the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] in 2006<ref name=\"Simmons criticizes donations\">{{cite web|title= GOP's Simmons, Caligiuri Criticize Linda McMahon For Donating More Than $35,000 To Democratic Candidates|author= Christopher Keating|date= October 11, 2009|accessdate= 2009-10-11|url= http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2009/10/gops-simmons-caligiuri-critici.html#more|publisher= The Courant|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100516051352/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2009/10/gops-simmons-caligiuri-critici.html#more|archive-date= May 16, 2010|url-status= dead|df= mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|presidential win]].<ref name=\"new yorker Emanuel\">{{cite magazine|title= The Gatekeeper: Rahm Emanuel on the job|author= Ryan Lizza|url= http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2009/03/02/090302fa_fact_lizza?currentPage=4|magazine=The New Yorker|date= 2009-03-02|accessdate= 2009-10-11}}</ref> McMahon explained to voters that her donations to Emanuel were on behalf of Rahm's brother, [[Ari Emanuel]], who had represented WWE in [[Hollywood]] since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |last=Stuart |first=Christine |url=http://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/election_2010/senate_candidate_talks_about_p.php |title=Senate Candidate Talks About Past ContributionsOpponents React |publisher=CT News Junkie |date=October 9, 2009 |accessdate=2010-02-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213071005/http://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/election_2010/senate_candidate_talks_about_p.php |archivedate=December 13, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>Tinley, James. (March 26, 2010) [http://www.nhregister.com/articles/2010/03/26/news/milford/doc4bacd909d0d10771049552.txt \"Milford Republicans courted by McMahon in Senate quest (video)\"] ''New Haven Register''. Retrieved 2010-03-27.</ref> According to McMahon, in 2002, \"He (Ari) called me one day and he said, my brother is running for Congress in Illinois. It happened to be Rahm. I didn't know Rahm.\" McMahon made more donations over the course of the next several years, including one check she wrote when Rahm Emanuel came to WWE headquarters to meet her.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ABSFY9Pn-2M&feature=player_embedded |title=Linda McMahon Discusses Donations To Rahm Emanuel And Liberal Democrats |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon's spokesperson clarified that McMahon didn't know who Rahm Emanuel was in '02, but was aware of his partisan status in '06.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shufflebarger |first=Jamie |url=http://hotlineoncall.nationaljournal.com/archives/2010/03/emanuel_becomes.php |title=Emanuel Becomes An Issue in CT GOP Race \u2013 Hotline on Call |work=National Journal |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100404060013/http://hotlineoncall.nationaljournal.com/archives/2010/03/emanuel_becomes.php |archive-date=April 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Wrestling in the spotlight====\n[[Image:Superstar Billy Graham.jpg|thumb|140px|right|Billy Graham, a former wrestler, was an outspoken critic of McMahon's campaign]]\nIn November 2009, former wrestler [[Superstar Billy Graham]] became an outspoken critic of McMahon's campaign. He said the McMahons were hypocrites for \"toning down\" the violence and sexuality in pro wrestling after many years of showing adult themes.<ref name=\"political smackdown\">{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/news/ctpolitics/hc-mcmahon-opposition-1118.artnov18,0,3727835.story|title= Political Smackdown: Former Wrestler Takes On McMahon|date= November 18, 2009|author=Christopher Keating|newspaper=The Hartford Courant|accessdate= 2010-02-07}}</ref> He launched Internet videos on WrestleView saying the WWE's switch to PG was politically motivated: \"...they (Linda and Vince) are doing it strictly to get Linda McMahon elected to Senator of Connecticut\", he stated in one video.<ref>{{cite web|title=Superstar Billy Graham Talks WWE's PG Rating |url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/interviews/video/superstar-billy-graham-talks-wwes-pg-rating-94161 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107013424/http://www.wrestlezone.com/interviews/video/superstar-billy-graham-talks-wwes-pg-rating-94161 |archivedate=January 7, 2010 }}</ref> Billy Graham contracted [[Hepatitis C]] from another wrestler's blood during his time in WWE and required a life-saving liver transplant as a result.<ref name=\"political smackdown\"/> When speaking about Linda, he said, \"She may look like a Sunday school teacher. Linda McMahon's hands are as bloody as her husband's because she is aware of every move in the ring. She has had no problem with grown men\u2014myself included\u2014cutting their head with a razor blade. All of a sudden, why aren't these guys bleeding anymore? Because Linda is running for the Senate.\" Graham told reporters that he was furious about having no pension and no health care after his wrestling career with WWE.<ref name=\"political smackdown\"/>\n\nMcMahon's campaign responded directly to Graham's accusations, saying he was a \"self-confessed liar\". On November 12, The campaign sent a letter directly to WrestleView, where Billy Graham had posted videos, attacking his credibility.<ref>Paglino, Nick. (November 12, 2009)[http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/article/exclusive-wwe-responds-to-billy-grahams-pg-allegations-90263 WWE responds to Billy Graham's PG-allegations] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109045534/http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/article/exclusive-wwe-responds-to-billy-grahams-pg-allegations-90263 |date=January 9, 2010 }} WrestleZone.com. Retrieved 2010-03-31.</ref> The campaign circulated an apology letter<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cdn.springboard.gorillanation.com/storage/wrestlezone.com/upl_images/pdf/BGrahamLetter.pdf|title=Graham apology}}</ref> Graham had written to the company in 1996, saying \"he has a habit of making false statements when he's not on WWE's payroll\". In the letter, Graham had admitted to making unjustified verbal attacks following his termination in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/70969-mcmahons-rise-puts-wrestlings-dangerous-history-in-the-spotlight|title=Linda McMahon's rise puts wrestling's dangerous history in the spotlight|date=December 7, 2009}}</ref><ref>Bix. (November 25, 2009) [http://www.cagesideseats.com/2009/11/25/1173840/linda-mcmahon-for-senator-roundup Linda McMahon for Senate Roundup] CageSideSeats Blog. Retrieved 2010-03-31.</ref>  Graham later reached out to apologize to McMahon for his comments, even offering to be a representative for her campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/2011-03-31/news/billy-graham-made-it-big-in-wrestling-now-the-steroids-that-got-him-there-may-be-killing-him/4/ |title=Superstar Billy Graham Made It Big in Wrestling \u2013 Now the Steroids That Got Him There May Be Killing Him |date=March 31, 2011 |last=Pratt |first=Gregory |page=5 |work=[[Phoenix New Times]] |accessdate=May 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====McMahon-Simmons rivalry====\nMcMahon and Simmons engaged in negative campaigning in November 2009.<ref name=\"upcomingdebates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/Game-on-McMahon-Simmons-and-Schiff-gear-up-for-339135.php|title=Game on: McMahon, Simmons and Schiff gear up for debate|author=Neil Vigdor|work=Connecticut Post |date=January 27, 2010|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref><ref name=\"eugene\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/02/linda-mcmahon-fights-back-euge.html?icid=sphere_tribune_hartfordcourant_inline|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119174455/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/02/linda-mcmahon-fights-back-euge.html?icid=sphere_tribune_hartfordcourant_inline|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 19, 2013|title=Linda McMahon fights back: Eugene was \"inspirational\"|author=Daniela Altimari|date=February 5, 2010|publisher=The Hartford Courant Blogs|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> In one political mailing, McMahon portrayed Simmons to the [[Tea Party movement]] as a fraud.<ref>Klein, Rick. (February 1, 2010) [http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2010/02/rob-simmons-and-the-power-of-tea-bags----top-line-candidate-corner.html Rob Simmons and the Power of Tea Bags \u2013 \u2018Top Line\u2019 Candidate Corner]</ref>  (Simmons had courted Tea Party conservatives, and even carried a tea bag in his pocket<ref>[http://vodpod.com/watch/2337358-gop-senate-candidate-rob-simmons-boasts-of-adding-a-tea-bag-to-the-constitution during the campaign trail] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110002725/http://vodpod.com/watch/2337358-gop-senate-candidate-rob-simmons-boasts-of-adding-a-tea-bag-to-the-constitution |date=January 10, 2010 }}</ref>)<ref>{{cite web|author=Lee Fang |url=http://thinkprogress.org/2009/10/14/simmons-tea-bag/ |title=GOP Senate Candidate Rob Simmons Boasts of Adding A Tea Bag to the Constitution |website=Think Progress |date=October 14, 2009 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> In December, a [[Washington Times]] article suggested that Simmons' appeals to conservatives were insincere,<ref>Carpenter, Amanda. (December 9, 2009) [http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/dec/09/hot-button-19487319/?page=2 'Tea Party' poser?] Washington Times. Accessed 2010-03-26 Linda McMahon Press Release. Greenwich Blog of Record. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref> pointing to his past support for \"[[Emissions trading|cap and trade]]\" and \"[[card check]]\", two [[hot button issue]]s for the Tea Party.<ref>Patru, Ed. (December 10, 2009) [http://greenwichroundup.blogspot.com/2009/12/121009-greenwich-resident-linda-mcmahon.html Greenwich resident Linda McMahon is gaining momentum]</ref> McMahon's campaign savaged this apparent flip-flop, sending mailings to Connecticut voters highlighting the issue. This hurt Simmons' standing among conservatives and labor unions.<ref>Vigdor, Neil. (March 24, 2010)[http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/default/article/Simmons-conservative-credentials-called-into-421404.php#page-1 Simmons' conservative credentials called into question by union bosses] Stamford Advocate. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref>\n\n[[Image:Eugene.jpg|thumb|160px|right|Rob Simmons circulated YouTube videos of Eugene, a mentally challenged wrestler, in his negative campaigning against McMahon]]\n\nSimmons focused later advertising on criticizing McMahon and the WWE.<ref>[http://joinrobsimmons.com/accountability McMahon WWE Accountability Clock] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100508011838/http://joinrobsimmons.com/accountability |date=May 8, 2010 }}</ref> Many times, Simmons accused McMahon of trying to \"buy the election\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-01-01/news/hc-mcmahon-money-0101.artjan01_1_republican-senate-candidate-linda-mcmahon-well-heeled-partisans|title=Rob Simmons Says Linda McMahon Is Using Donations To Try To Buy Support}}</ref> In January, he circulated YouTube videos of wrestler [[Eugene (wrestler)|Eugene]] being humiliated on-screen, claiming the WWE was insensitive to the mentally challenged. The McMahon campaign countered, saying Eugene, rather than being ridiculed, was an inspirational character who ultimately became \"a hero\".\n\nSimmons launched negative ads attacking WWE's history of [[steroid abuse]],<ref>Rob Simmons for U.S. Senate (March 4, 2010) [https://web.archive.org/web/20120320060610/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/Letter%20to%20McMahon%20from%20Simmons_030410.pdf 10 Questions for Linda McMahon]</ref> its record of [[List of premature professional wrestling deaths|premature wrestler deaths]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/WWE_News_3/article_40140.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - WWE News: Linda McMahon's Senate opponent circulating video on high number of deceased wrestlers from WrestleMania 7 PPV (w/VIDEO)|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref> and circulated some of WWE's most [[political correctness|politically incorrect]] segments.<ref name=\"eugene\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T9oQFX0qHz0 |title= WWE Sandman beats the hell out of Eugene|author=DavidDH1996 (YouTube User)|date=December 17, 2008|publisher= YouTube.com|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref><ref>Lockhart, Brian. (February 12, 2010) [http://blog.ctnews.com/politicalcapitol/2010/02/12/norwalk-mayor-moccia-wants-mcmahon-simmons-to-turn-down-the-heat/ Norwalk Mayor Moccia wants McMahon, Simmons to turn down the heat] CT News. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref> By March 2010, the Simmons campaign had gone so negative that some established Connecticut Republicans began to denounce his attacks.<ref>Lockhart, Brian. 2010-02-21.[http://www.newstimes.com/news/article/Simmons-camp-has-concerns-about-GOP-chairman-374686.php#page-1 Simmons camp has 'concerns' about GOP chairman Healy]. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref><ref>Wright, Chase. (March 26, 2010)[http://www.thehour.com/story/484062 Moccia endorses McMahon for U.S. Senate] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717010056/http://www.thehour.com/story/484062 |date=July 17, 2011 }} The Hour Online. Retrieved 2010-03-26.</ref>\n\n===2010===\n\n====Blumenthal replaces Dodd====\n\nOn January 7, just hours after Chris Dodd announced his retirement, the [[Democratic State Central Committee of Connecticut|Connecticut Democratic Party]] launched [[Richard Blumenthal]], the Attorney General, as its new candidate.<ref name=\"dem press conference\">{{cite web|title= Richard Blumenthal for Senate Press Conference|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q7N-IrqptEU|author= CTBlogger (YouTube user)|accessdate= 2010-01-08|publisher=YouTube.com}}</ref> Blumenthal, who had a job approval rating over 80%, enjoyed near-unanimous support from Democrats and was considered a formidable opponent for any statewide office.<ref>Applebome, Peter. (January 6, 2010) [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/07/nyregion/07towns.html Smackdown for the Senate Takes a Twist] New York Times. Retrieved 2010-03-27.</ref>\n\nAlthough Connecticut is considered a solid Democratic-voting state, McMahon and Simmons sought to capitalize on the anti-establishment and anti-Democratic tide that had become a factor in the 2010 campaign season.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/01/connecticut-republicans-bask-i.html|title= Connecticut Republicans bask in glow of Scott Brown's win|author= Daniela Altimari|newspaper= Hartford Courant|date= January 19, 2010|accessdate= 2010-01-23|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://archive.today/20120707220922/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/01/connecticut-republicans-bask-i.html|archivedate= July 7, 2012|df= mdy-all}}</ref> In particular, [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]]'s [[United States Senate special election in Massachusetts, 2010|win in Massachusetts]] was seen as a good [[omen]] for Republicans nationally, as it showed that a Republican could win in a \"deep blue\" state.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b63HP13Lrkc|title= Linda McMahon on The View|publisher= YouTube|date= January 21, 2010|accessdate= 2010-01-23}}</ref> A key factor in Brown's win had been his demand for fiscal responsibility, which McMahon made her centerpiece issue, attacking Simmons for his voting record as U.S. Representative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linda2010.com/press-releases/2010/01/youre-no-scott-brown/ |title=You're No Scott Brown |publisher=Linda For Senate press releases |date=January 20, 2010 |accessdate=2010-02-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001140446/http://www.linda2010.com/press-releases/2010/01/youre-no-scott-brown/ |archivedate=October 1, 2010 }}</ref> In new mailings, she pointed to Simmons' D-rating from the [[National Taxpayers Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://blog.ctnews.com/politicalcapitol/2010/01/20/mcmahon-simmons-bicker-over-whos-more-like-scott-brown/#comments|title = McMahon, Simmons bicker over who's Scott Brown-ier|author= Brian Lockhart|date= January 20, 2010|accessdate= 2010-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, while Blumenthal continued to lead all Republican contenders by 20\u201330 points, McMahon took frontrunner status from Simmons.<ref>Pazniokas, Mark. (March 19, 2010) [http://ctmirror.com/story/5215/mcmahons-investment-produces-its-first-returns McMahon's Investment produces its first Returns] [[CT Mirror]]. Retrieved 2010-03-25.</ref><ref>Schwartz, Douglas. [http://www.quinnipiac.edu/x1296.xml?ReleaseID=1433 McMahon Wrestles To The Top In GOP Senate Race, Quinnipiac University Connecticut Poll Finds; Blumenthal Hammers Her 2-1] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322195015/http://www.quinnipiac.edu/x1296.xml?ReleaseID=1433 |date=March 22, 2010 }} Quinnipiac University. Published March 17, 2010. Retrieved March 25, 2010.</ref> Her rise in the polls was attributed largely to her heavy media presence, as a polling researcher pointed out, \"You can't miss her television ads. They're everywhere. She's the only candidate for Senate that's on TV right now.\"<ref name=\"march10pointlead\">Vigdor, Neil. (March 18, 2010) [http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/default/article/McMahon-overtakes-Simmons-in-latest-GOP-Senate-411714.php#page-1 McMahon overtakes Simmons in latest GOP Senate Poll] Stamford Advocate. Retrieved 2010-03-25.</ref> Political research showed that McMahon had gained strong popularity with female voters,<ref>Altimari, Daniela. (March 18, 2010) [http://articles.courant.com/2010-03-18/news/hc-capitol-watch-link-gop-poll-0317_1_linda-mcmahon-world-wrestling-entertainment-ceo-republican-women Linda McMahon has GOP Women in her Corner] Hartford Courant Blogs. Retrieved 2010-03-25.</ref> social conservatives,<ref>Altimari, Daniela. [http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/03/for-social-conservatives-the-m.html For Social Conservatives, \"the math points to Linda McMahon\"] {{webarchive|url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120926211749/http%3A//blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/03/for%2Dsocial%2Dconservatives%2Dthe%2Dm.html |date=September 26, 2012 }} Hartford Courant Blogs. Published March 25, 2010. Retrieved March 25, 2010.</ref> and residents in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]].<ref name=\"march10pointlead\"/>\n\n====April controversies====\nIn articles published by the ''New London Day'' and ''[[Politico.com]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100410/NWS12/304109913|title=McMahon warned doctor of probe|website=The Day}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/stories/0410/35599.html|title=Memo: McMahon tipped steroid doctor|first=Glenn|last=Thrush|website=POLITICO}}</ref> McMahon's controversial \"tip-off\" memo resurfaced, raising new questions regarding her ethical judgment. The 1989 memo asked a WWE executive to \"clue in\" a company doctor to possible legal action he might face from the Federal government.<ref name=\"1989memo\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/assets/pdf/NL7163449.PDF|title=McMahon's 1989 Memo}}</ref> At the time, the FBI was investigating the doctor for selling steroids to WWF wrestlers, including [[Vince McMahon]].\n\nThe timing of her memo was suspicious, as the investigation did not become public knowledge until May 27, 1990, the day of the doctor's arrest. When the articles were published, Linda did not respond, but WWE did, telling reporters that McMahon only wanted the doctor \"clued in\" so he would know why he was fired.<ref name=\"Lindasrole\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-mcmahon_memo_0410.artapr10,0,2139987.story|title=Memo raises questions about role in 1989 case}}</ref> WWE said McMahon learned of the investigation through a company lawyer who had heard the Federal prosecutor involved, James West, carelessly talking about the case at a fundraising event.<ref name=\"Lindasrole\"/> West said the WWE's story was a lie,<ref name=\"wwe-west explanation\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100411/NWS12/304119975|title=Ex-prosecutor says McMahon camp wrong on WWF warning|website=The Day}}</ref> denying ever discussing the case or attending the event in question.<ref name=\"wwe-west explanation\"/><ref name=\"wwe-west explanation\"/><ref>Sex, Lies, and Headlocks. p. 92</ref> Although West and WWE continued to point fingers, McMahon and her campaign did not publicly discuss the story and its ongoing controversy. The news hurt McMahon's public image<ref>{{cite news |author=Anonymous |url=http://www.norwichbulletin.com/Opinion/x57953354/Our-view-McMahon-owes-state-an-explanation |title=Our view: McMahon owes state an explanation \u2013 Norwich, CT |newspaper=Norwich Bulletin |date=April 16, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120907035617/http://www.norwichbulletin.com/Opinion/x57953354/Our-view-McMahon-owes-state-an-explanation |archivedate=September 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and, according to her critics, it provided evidence she had tried to \"undermine a criminal investigation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100412/NWS12/100419955|title=Simmons goes on the attack|website=The Day}}</ref>\n\nAn article published in the ''[[Stamford Advocate]]'' raised attention to McMahon's voter registration drive at the [[University of Connecticut]], where college students were to be paid a $5 bonus for each voter they registered as a Republican.<ref name=\"$5votes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Paying-for-voters-McMahon-campaign-plan-draws-460248.php#page-1|title= Paying for voters: McMahon campaign plan draws questions|author=Brian Lockhart|newspaper=Stamford Advocate|date=April 23, 2010}}</ref> The potential [[moral hazard]] in such a program created negative associations to [[Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now|ACORN]]'s [[Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now#2008: Presidential campaign|2008 controversy]] regarding invalid voter applications. Although the practice was not illegal,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/local/article/Paying-for-voters-McMahon-campaign-plan-draws-460927.php |title=Paying for voters? McMahon campaign plan draws questions \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=April 24, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> the bonus structure was removed from the drive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailycampus.com/news/mcmahon-under-fire-for-voter-bounties-1.1434516|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719141324/http://www.dailycampus.com/news/mcmahon-under-fire-for-voter-bounties-1.1434516|url-status=dead|title=McMahon under fire for voter 'bounties'|archivedate=July 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-04-27/news/hc-ct-mcmahon-voters-0427.artapr27_1_linda-mcmahon-voter-registration-voter-fraud|title=Linda McMahon Withdraws Bonus Offer For Voter Registration}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com/2010/04/mcmahon-campaign-cancels-money-for-gop-registrations-voter-drive.php?ref=mp|title=McMahon Campaign Cancels Money-For-GOP Registrations Voter Drive &#124; Talking Points Memo|date=April 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====''New York Times'' Vietnam story====\n{{Main|Richard Blumenthal#New York Times Vietnam story}}\n[[Image:Richard Blumenthal  speaking with Scott Slifka.jpg|thumb|230px|right|[[Richard Blumenthal]], left, was the Democratic nominee for the U.S. Senate. During her campaign, McMahon capitalized on faulty statements he made about his Vietnam service]]\nMcMahon focused her attention towards the presumptive Democratic challenger in the few weeks before the convention. On May 12, she launched political TV ads on Blumenthal's apparent [[flip-flop (politics)|flip-flop]] on [[Political Action Committee|PAC contributions]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/news/local/statewire/hc-ap-ct-connsenatemay12,0,783402.story |title=McMahon ad targets Blumenthal in Conn. Senate race |access-date=June 3, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515140653/http://www.courant.com/news/local/statewire/hc-ap-ct-connsenatemay12,0,783402.story |archive-date=May 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On May 17, a ''[[New York Times]]'' story revealed that Blumenthal had [[Richard Blumenthal#Controversy surrounding statements of service in Vietnam|made false claims]] about his military service during the [[War in Vietnam]].\n\nOn May 19, McMahon said that she played a role in the ''New York Times'' story<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyructions.com/mcmahon-strikes-turns-blumenthal-into-bruce-caputo/|title=McMahon Strikes. Turns Blumenthal into Bruce Caputo.}}</ref> and confirmed that her campaign helped uncover the facts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/news/breaking/hc-mcmahon-admits-campaign-role-times-blumenthal,0,7678442.story|title=McMahon Confirms Campaign's Role In N.Y. Times Story On Blumenthal}}</ref> Her campaign sent a video of Blumenthal's questionable speech to the newspaper. Days later, McMahon's campaign posted a full version of that speech on YouTube, which showed Blumenthal clearly explaining his \"Vietnam era\" service early in his speech, clearing the discrepancy.<ref name=\"McMahon softens blow\">{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/right-now/2010/05/linda_mcmahon_campaign_acciden.html |title=Right Now \u2013 Linda McMahon campaign accidentally softens the blow of Blumenthal story |publisher=Voices.washingtonpost.com |date=May 19, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> The full version was a godsend for the Blumenthal campaign, and it softened the blow dealt by his later \"in Vietnam\" gaffe.<ref name=\"McMahon softens blow\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100520/NWS12/305209466|title=Video mitigates Blumenthal remarks|website=The Day}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/05/blumenthal-and-vietnam-the-dir.html|archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20111113071932/http%3A//blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/05/blumenthal%2Dand%2Dvietnam%2Dthe%2Ddir.html|url-status=dead|title=Blumenthal and Vietnam, the Director's cut|archivedate=November 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-blumenthal-folo-0520-20100520-story.html|title=Blumenthal Counters With Longer Version Of Video|first=By DANIELA|last=ALTIMARI|website=courant.com}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon's campaign spokesman, Ed Patru, later told reporters that the campaign strategically \"put its fingerprints\" on the story to impress Republican delegates before the convention.<ref name=\"the smackdown candidate\"/>\n\n====Republican convention====\nMcMahon, Schiff, and Simmons competed for the nomination at the convention on May 21, 2010.<ref name=\"RepConvention\">Jacobs, Jeremy P. (2010\u201301) Politics (Campaigns & Elections). Reds and Blues: State Spotlight \u2013 Connecticut. January 2010 issue, Vol. 31, Issue 1, p51</ref><ref>[http://www.newstimes.com/local/article/In-the-face-of-doubters-Simmons-Senate-campaign-470114.php In the face of doubters, Simmons' Senate campaign projecting optimism in buildup to GOP convention]</ref> Prior to the Convention, McMahon had urged supporters to register for the Republican primary, suggesting that she would run even if she had not won the Republican nomination.<ref name=\"LindaStrategy\"/> Schiff similarly had indicated that he would run regardless of the convention's results.<ref>{{cite web |last=Toeplitz |first=Shira |url=http://blogs.cqpolitics.com/eyeon2010/2010/03/schiff-hits-the-air-without-th.html |title=Schiff Hits The Air \u2013 Without The (R) \u2013 The Eye (CQ Politics) |publisher=Blogs.cqpolitics.com |date=March 29, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331110751/http://blogs.cqpolitics.com/eyeon2010/2010/03/schiff-hits-the-air-without-th.html |archivedate=March 31, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nSimmons, the ostensible Party favorite, staked his campaign on the convention and said repeatedly he would not \"force a primary\" if he lost the convention.<ref name=\"LindaStrategy\">{{cite web|url=http://ctlocalpolitics.net//2010/02/01/mcmahons-strategy-has-simmons-camp-on-ropes/|title= McMahon's Strategy Has Simmons' Camp on Ropes|author=Vincent (blogger)|date=February 1, 2010|publisher=Connecticut Local politics|accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> However, when Simmons lost many of his pledged delegates to McMahon, his viability was doubted by the media and state GOP.<ref>[http://cookpolitical.com/node/3343 Connecticut Senate: Can McMahon Topple Blumenthal?] Cook Political Report. April 29, 2010.</ref><ref name=\"simmonsprojects\"/><ref>[http://blog.joinrobsimmons.com/14-days-til-convention-and-the-momentum-is-growing/ Rob Simmons \u2013 14 days til convention and the momentum is growing!]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Pundits revealed that Simmons was under pressure to drop out and run for [[Connecticut's 2nd congressional district|his former Congressional seat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtnh.com/dpp/news/connecticut/ct%27s-senate%2C-attorney-general-campaigns|title=CT's Senate, Attorney General campaigns|publisher=WTNH.com Channel 8 News|date=January 12, 2010|accessdate=2010-02-09}}</ref> When Simmons was asked about the possibility,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/video/top-line-tea-partys-candidate-connecticut-9719867|title=Video: Tea Party's Candidate in Connecticut|website=ABC News}}</ref> he did not explicitly \"rule out\" a change in races.<ref name=\"Simmonsruleout\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2010/02/simmons-wont-rule-out-run-for-former-house-seat.html|title= Simmons Won't Rule Out Run for Former House Seat|publisher=The Note : ABC News|author=Rick Klein|date= February 1, 2010|accessdate=2010-02-09}}</ref> Simmons was visibly frustrated by the negative media publicity he received as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100207/NWS12/302079934/1018|title=Simmons brings new perspectives to Senate race|author=Ted Mann|publisher=The Day|date=February 7, 2010|accessdate=2010-02-09}}</ref> Simmons then claimed that he had more delegates than McMahon by a wide margin.<ref name=\"simmonsprojects\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newstimes.com/local/article/In-the-face-of-doubters-Simmons-Senate-campaign-470114.php|title=In the face of doubters, Simmons' Senate campaign projecting optimism in buildup to GOP convention|author=Neil Vigdor|date=April 30, 2010}}</ref> McMahon heavily outspent Simmons, maintaining a steady lead over both her rivals. Simmons could not fund TV ads after a drop in fundraising.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0110/32212.html|title=Simmons' 4Q fundraising drops off|author=Josh Kraushaar|publisher=Politico.com|date=January 29, 2010|accessdate= 2010-02-09}}</ref> In the weeks prior to the convention, Simmons failed to regain in the polls.<ref name=\"simmons and 1992\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100425/OP04/304259942|title=Simmons versus the checkbook|author=Paul Choiniere|publisher=The Day|date=April 25, 2010|accessdate=2010-01-25}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = State Republican Convention results (first round)<ref name=\"politico1\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = '''Linda McMahon'''*\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = '''737'''\n| percentage = '''51.76'''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Rob Simmons*\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 632\n| percentage = 44.62\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Peter Schiff\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 44\n| percentage = 3.11\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Vincent Forras\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 7\n| percentage = 0.49\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Ethan Book\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 0\n| percentage = 0.00\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 1,414\n| percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n<small>* Denotes candidate met the minimum threshold of 15 percent to appear on the primary ballot</small>\n\n<small>* 708 delegates were required to win endorsement from the Republican Party</small><ref name=\"the smackdown candidate\">{{cite magazine|last=Rice |first=Andrew |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/10_24/b4182066684319.htm |title=The Smackdown Candidate |magazine=BusinessWeek |date=June 3, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n\nSchiff was polling at roughly 10% days before the convention and told many of his pledged delegates at the convention to switch to Simmons \"because I didn't think McMahon was playing fair.\" Schiff told his supporters that McMahon's campaign had about 40 members on the convention floor attempting to garner more support while votes were being cast, breaking convention rules.<ref name=conventionupdate>{{cite video\n | people      = Peter Schiff\n | date        = May 22, 2010\n | title       = Schiff for Senate \u2013 Republican convention results\n | url         = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=koiXvCzvGlw\n | format      = Video blog\n | medium      = Flash\n | publisher   = Schiff Report\n | location    = [[Stamford, Connecticut]]\n | accessdate  = 2010-05-23\n}}</ref>\n\nSimmons was deeply disappointed to lose on the first round of voting.<ref name=\"simmons politico interview\"/> Despite his promise to the contrary, Simmons then decided to force a primary with McMahon.<ref name=\"politico1\">{{cite web|author=Andy Barr | url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0510/37633.html | title=McMahon wins GOP nod in Conn. \u2013 Shira Toeplitz and Maggie Haberman |publisher=Politico.Com |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Four days later, on May 25, Simmons reversed himself again, and suspended his campaign, saying he could not compete financially with McMahon's deep pockets.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/26/nyregion/26simmons.html | work=The New York Times | title=Simmons Suspends Campaign for Connecticut Senate | first=Raymond | last=Hernandez | date=May 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ctmirror1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6241/gop-defies-history-primaries |title=Republican hopefuls no longer deferring to convention delegates' decision &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=June 1, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604072032/http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6241/gop-defies-history-primaries |archivedate=June 4, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Simmons-ends-campaign-but-stays-on-ballot-499060.php#page-2 |title=Simmons: Grudging retreat, but no surrender \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=May 25, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Although Simmons was no longer campaigning, he often disparaged McMahon to the press. He told [[The National Review]] that he did not think McMahon \"can win at all\". He also said that if she were to ask for his help, he would say he was \"preoccupied\".<ref>Costa, Robert. (May 26, 2010) [http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ODkxZmFlMmM4OTRkNTUwMjgwYzYzM2EwODkxNjc0ZjY Hard Feelings in Hartford] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527220917/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ODkxZmFlMmM4OTRkNTUwMjgwYzYzM2EwODkxNjc0ZjY |date=May 27, 2010 }}</ref> Simmons said he did McMahon a favor by stopping his campaign, but he did not endorse her.<ref name=\"simmons politico interview\"/> He said he would not call off the August primary because \"voters deserve another choice.\"<ref name=\"simmons politico interview\">{{cite web |last=Toeplitz |first=Shira |url=http://dyn.politico.com/printstory.cfm?uuid=D711A3F5-18FE-70B2-A8A50E72F3709E4F |title=Simmons 'sorry' for ripping McMahon \u2013 POLITICO.com Print View |publisher=Dyn.politico.com |date=May 26, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100731035311/http://dyn.politico.com/printstory.cfm?uuid=D711A3F5-18FE-70B2-A8A50E72F3709E4F |archive-date=July 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Many of Simmons' hardcore backers also refused to back McMahon.<ref name=\"theday1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100528/NWS01/305289957/-1/NWS |title=Peter Schiff tackling McMahon momentum &#124; News from southeastern Connecticut |publisher=The Day |date=May 28, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref name=\"theday1\"/>\n\nIn late July, Simmons re-entered the race by airing ads on TV reminding Republican primary goers that he was still on the ballot, as well as by participating in debates and editorial board discussions.<ref name=SimmonsReturns/>\n\n====Republican primary====\n[[Image:SchiffSpeaking.png|thumb|left|140px|Peter Schiff, who failed to gain 15% of Republican support at the Republican Convention, collected petitions to challenge her in an August Primary]]\nIn the weeks after her victory at the Republican Convention, McMahon fared poorly in political polls<ref name=\"25 points behind\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100603/INTERACT010403/100609881 |title=Linda McMahon: Jury's still out on steroid risks &#124; News from southeastern Connecticut |publisher=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McClarin |first=Jim |url=http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/06/the-week-from-heck-for-linda-m.html |title=The Week From Heck For Linda McMahon \u2013 Rick Green &#124; CT Confidential |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707065029/http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/06/the-week-from-heck-for-linda-m.html |archivedate=July 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and suffered from high unfavorability ratings among both Democrats and Republicans.<ref>{{cite web |last=Snyder |first=Mike |url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/05/q-poll-blumenthal-trumps-mcmah.html |title=Q Poll: Blumenthal trumps McMahon by 25 points; voters shrug off Vietnam matter \u2013 Capitol Watch |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120930043930/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/05/q-poll-blumenthal-trumps-mcmah.html |archivedate=September 30, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Cook Political Report]] attributed much of the damage in her public image to months of criticism from Simmons and the media.<ref name=\"june cook political\">{{cite web|url=http://cookpolitical.com/node/3343 |title=2010 Senate \u2013 CT &#124; The Cook Political Report |publisher=Cookpolitical.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article7144836.ece|title=timesonline.co.uk|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=June 6, 2010}}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> On June 8, McMahon released her own [[political polling|internal polling]] to assure Republicans she was competitive with Blumenthal.<ref name=\"polling with a twist\">http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6366/spin-twist-mcmahon-says-her-polling-close-blumenthals Spin with a twist: McMahon says her polling is close to Blumenthal's</ref>\n\nNonetheless, negative sentiment towards McMahon fueled some momentum for both Simmons and Schiff.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/political-landscape-murky-elections-connecticut-hawaii/story?id=10729055 |title=Political Landscape Gets Murky After Elections in Connecticut, Hawaii \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Some Republican voters who had supported Simmons turned to Schiff, who shared their resentment towards McMahon and the convention.<ref>{{cite web|last=Miller |first=Sean J. |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/101243-blumenthal-more-popular-in-wake-of-media-storm |title=Blumenthal more popular in wake of media storm \u2013 The Hill's Ballot Box |publisher=Thehill.com |date= June 3, 2010|accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Hazlett |first=Bob |url=http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/06/schiff-neck-and-neck-with-mcm.html |title=Peter Schiff on Linda McMahon: 'I Will Be the Frontrunner.' \u2013 Rick Green &#124; CT Confidential |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120708111010/http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/06/schiff-neck-and-neck-with-mcm.html |archivedate=July 8, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rasmussenreports.com/public_content/politics/elections/election_2010/election_2010_senate_elections/connecticut/toplines/toplines_connecticut_senate_june_1_2010|title=Toplines - Connecticut Senate - June 1, 2010 - Rasmussen Reports\u00ae|website=www.rasmussenreports.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Katz |first=Marisa |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/postpartisan/2010/05/twisting_the_truth_in_the_conn.html |title=PostPartisan \u2013 Twisting the truth in the Connecticut Senate race |publisher=Voices.washingtonpost.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Schiff fared poorly in the convention, but collected over 10,000 signatures from Connecticut residents was placing him on the primary ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Schiff-enlists-paid-consulting-firm-to-help-507943.php |title=Schiff enlists paid consulting firm to help collect signatures \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=June 1, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Schiff-lives-to-fight-another-day-against-McMahon-532070.php |title=Schiff lives to fight another day against McMahon \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=June 21, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Mothersopposingmcmahon.jpeg|thumb|right|Mothers Opposing McMahon, a [[527 group]], was established in July 2010]]\nMcMahon spent the remainder of June and July attempting to control the wrestling element of her public image, which repeatedly received negative media attention.<ref>{{cite news|last=Condon |first=Stephanie |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20008911-503544.html |title=Linda McMahon Airs Ad Featuring WWE History \u2013 Political Hotsheet |publisher=CBS News |date=June 25, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> On June 22, McMahon's campaign gained unwanted attention\n<ref>{{cite web |author=WrestlingNewsWorld.com |url=http://www.wrestlingnewsworld.com/wwe-news/linda-mcmahon-trends-yahoo-in-lieu-of-lawsuit.php |title=Linda McMahon Trends Yahoo in Lieu of Lawsuit |publisher=Wrestlingnewsworld.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718122346/http://www.wrestlingnewsworld.com/wwe-news/linda-mcmahon-trends-yahoo-in-lieu-of-lawsuit.php |archive-date=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> from a lawsuit filed by [[Martha Hart]], the wife of deceased wrestler [[Owen Hart]], in regard to a wrestling DVD featuring her husband.<ref name=\"martha hart sues\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6527/mcmahon-being-sued-widow-former-wrestler |title=McMahon being sued by widow of former wrestler &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=June 22, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> The WWE said her lawsuit was \"meritless\", nothing more than a \"political hit job.\"<ref name=\"martha hart sues\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/sports/slapped+with+lawsuit+from+Canadian+wrestler+Owen+Hart+widow/3192093/story.html |title=WWE slapped with lawsuit from Canadian wrestler Owen Hart's widow |publisher=Vancouversun.com |date=June 23, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727221943/http://www.vancouversun.com/sports/slapped%2Bwith%2Blawsuit%2Bfrom%2BCanadian%2Bwrestler%2BOwen%2BHart%2Bwidow/3192093/story.html |archivedate=July 27, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amlawdaily.typepad.com/amlawdaily/2010/06/wwe-widow-suit.html |title=Nixon Peabody, K&L Gates Spar Over Wrestling Widow's Suit Against WWE and Senate Candidate |publisher=Amlawdaily.typepad.com |date=June 23, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.journalinquirer.com/articles/2010/06/23/politics_and_government/doc4c220ab77bc25756023144.txt|title=McMahon camp, WWE: Lawsuit is contract issue, political stunt|first=Susan HaighAssociated|last=Press|website=Journal Inquirer}}</ref> McMahon launched TV ads embracing her career in WWE, downplaying negative opinion of wrestling as a form of \"soap opera\" entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hVsM8hb-21TZfsamXPJ254_0w9JQD9GHSPO80|title=McMahon: Wrestling was soap opera|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628054936/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hVsM8hb-21TZfsamXPJ254_0w9JQD9GHSPO80|archivedate=June 28, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Davis |first=Susan |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/06/25/linda-mcmahon-talks-wwe-in-campaign-ad/ |title=Linda McMahon Talks WWE in Campaign Ad \u2013 Washington Wire \u2013 WSJ |publisher=Blogs.wsj.com |date=June 25, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Becker |first=Bernie |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/25/mcmahon-mentions-wrestling-in-new-ad/ |title=McMahon Mentions Wrestling in New Ad - The Caucus Blog - NYTimes.com |publisher=Thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com |date=June 25, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6554/mcmahons-new-ad-features-wrestling-call-shake-things |title=McMahon's new ad embraces controversial wrestling role &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=June 24, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703151008/http://www.ctmirror.org/story/6554/mcmahons-new-ad-features-wrestling-call-shake-things |archivedate=July 3, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In July 2010, five women from West Hartford attacked her wrestling career, saying WWE encouraged profane and violent treatment of women.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/07/14/linda-mcmahon-ct-senate-c_n_646347.html |title=Linda McMahon, CT Senate Candidate, Slammed By Mothers Group Over WWE Past (VIDEO) |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= July 14, 2010|accessdate=2010-08-14 |first=Jason |last=Linkins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.wnct.com/news/2010/jul/13/conn-moms-oppose-mcmahon-over-wrestling-ties-ar-298693/|title=Conn. Moms Oppose Mcmahon Over Wrestling Ties|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716190741/http://www2.wnct.com/news/2010/jul/13/conn-moms-oppose-mcmahon-over-wrestling-ties-ar-298693/|archive-date=July 16, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> The McMahon campaign dismissed their group, Mothers Opposing McMahon, as a group of [[political operative|Democratic operatives]], arguing that their press conference was organized and paid for by the [[Connecticut Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/07/15/mothers-group-slams-mcmahon-role-wwe-ceo/ |title=Dem Mothers' Group Slams McMahon Over Former Role as WWE CEO |publisher=FOXNews.com |date=April 7, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Nonetheless, McMahon's campaign continued to fend off attacks, such as the [[Linda McMahon#Tom Cole|Tom Cole affair]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Ben |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/bensmith/0710/McMahon_and_the_ring_boy.html |title=McMahon and the 'ring boy' \u2013 Ben Smith |publisher=Politico.Com |date=July 31, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> and when she pretended to kick [[Jim Ross]] before firing him as part of a WWE storyline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/08/06/wrestling-ceo-vince-mcmah_n_673703.html |title=Wrestling CEO Vince McMahon Sick of Wife Linda McMahon's Senate Smackdown |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=August 8, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n\n=====Primary results=====\nMcMahon won the Republican nomination on August 10 with 49% of the vote. Her win received a great deal of national attention, plenty of media coverage, and congratulatory calls from national Republicans [[Mitt Romney]] and [[John Cornyn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/McMahon-basks-in-congratulations-national-612600.php |title=McMahon basks in congratulations, national attention \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date= August 12, 2010|accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon also received calls from Schiff and Simmons offering their support.<ref name=\"mcmahon win\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100812/NWS12/308129474/1080/nws |title=Democrats deride McMahon win &#124; News from southeastern Connecticut |publisher=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon's lack of a majority was derided by critics as a sign that Republicans were not fully satisfied with her candidacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20100812/OP01/308129493 |title=Low turnout sets stage for big election &#124; News from southeastern Connecticut |publisher=The Day |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> Simmons said it was possible that Schiff was a spoiler in the campaign, [[vote splitting|siphoning off support]] that could have helped him defeat McMahon.<ref name=\"mcmahon win\"/>\n\n==General election==\nDuring the general election, McMahon campaigned in small towns and appeared with local Republicans, positioning herself as a [[populism|populist]] candidate against \"establishment\" figure Blumenthal.\n\n===Lance Cade's death===\n{{Wikinews|US professional wrestler Lance Cade dies aged 29}}\nThe death at age 29 from heart failure of former WWE wrestler, [[Lance Cade]], in August 2010 renewed controversy over WWE.<ref name=\"death renews focus\">\"http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/Wrestler-s-death-renews-focus-on-McMahon-WWE-619584.php</ref> Cade had abused painkillers and steroids during his career in WWE. When a reporter asked her about Cade, McMahon replied the WWE had no more ability to prevent his death \"than a studio could have prevented [[Heath Ledger]]'s death\".<ref name=\"the hill\"/> She also told the Connecticut Post \"I may have met him once\".<ref name=\"death renews focus\"/> Cade's father disputed McMahon's assertion of so distant a connection,<ref name=\"father blasts McMahon\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20100826/nws12/308269378|title=Dead wrestler's father blasts McMahon, WWE|website=The Day}}</ref> and her remarks prompted former WWE wrestler [[Christopher Nowinski]] to speak out against McMahon and the WWE.<ref name=\"nowinski interview\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/08/former-wrestler-mcmahon-kicking-dirt-on-the-grave-of-lance-cade/61782/ | title=Former Wrestler: McMahon 'Kicking Dirt on the Grave' of Lance Cade| date=August 19, 2010}}</ref> He alleged that the abuse of steroids and painkillers was encouraged and rewarded by the company, saying McMahon was \"just kicking dirt on the guy's grave.\"<ref name=\"nowinski interview\"/> He also related a conversation he'd had with Cade in which Cade expressed a desire to stop using steroids, but said, \"the pressure is to use them, because the WWE rewards the guys who use them.\"<ref name=\"death renews focus\"/><ref name=\"the hill\">{{Cite web | url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/114957-ex-wrestler-wwe-rewards-steroid-use-says-mcmahon-knew- |title = Wrestler's death puts spotlight on McMahon's WWE ties|date = August 19, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"nowinski interview\"/><ref name=\"wwe hits back\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/08/wwe-hits-back-at-nowinski/61851/|title=WWE Hits Back at Nowinski|date=August 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWWE quickly responded to Nowinski's accusations, saying, \"It is very dubious that he ever had a conversation with Lance Cade much less Lance Cade confiding to a total stranger that he used painkillers and steroids.\"<ref name=\"wwe hits back\"/> The company also sought to discredit Nowinski by claiming that he had failed to disclose that he'd suffered previous concussions before signing his contract with WWE, as was required.<ref name=\"wwe hits back\"/> They further disputed his claims as to the number of days wrestlers worked, on average, and observed that despite Nowinski's renown in the area of [[Chronic traumatic encephalopathy|CTE]], a form of brain injury resulting from repeated concussions, he is not an expert in matters relating to steroids or pain killers.<ref name=\"wwe hits back\"/> The charge that Nowinski was a \"stranger\" to Cade was refuted by Nowinski: He and Lance Cade had been tag team partners during 2002\u20132003, and co-workers until 2007.<ref name=\"the hill\"/>\n\n===Attacks on Blumenthal's credibility===\n{{quote|I've never taken PAC money, and I have rejected all special interest money because I have stood strong and taken legal action against many of those special interests|[[Richard Blumenthal]]|}}\n\nIn August 2010, McMahon damaged Blumenthal's credibility by publicizing an apparent [[flip-flop (politics)|flip-flop]] he made on PAC donations. She used both TV ads and mailers to portray him as \"dishonest\" for accepting over $480,000 in PAC money in 2010,<ref>http://www.ctmirror.org/story/7387/mcmahon-steps-attacks-blumenthalK{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> following $17,000 during the 1980s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hotair.com/archives/ed-morrissey/2010/08/23/blumenthal-took-pac-money-despite-claims-to-have-refused-it/|title=Blumenthal took PAC money despite claims to have refused it|date=August 23, 2010|website=Hot Air}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/08/mcmahon-chronicles-ii.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-08-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707071651/http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2010/08/mcmahon-chronicles-ii.html |archivedate=July 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\nIn October, McMahon aired TV ads comparing Blumenthal to departing Senator Chris Dodd and the corruption of the [[Countrywide financial political loan scandal|Countrywide scandal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://townhall.com/tipsheet/guybenson/2010/10/21/finally-mcmahon-ties-blumenthal-to-chris-dodd-in-connecticut-n715488|title=Finally: McMahon Ties Blumenthal to Chris Dodd in Connecticut|first=Guy|last=Benson|website=Townhall}}</ref><ref name=\"theatlanticwire.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/opinions/view/opinion/In-Connecticut-Race-McMahon-Spends-Blumenthal-Soars-5490|title=In Connecticut Race, McMahon Spends, Blumenthal Soars - The Atlantic|date=October 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Blumenthal-McMahon-trade-charges-in-second-debate-691441.php|title=Blumenthal, McMahon trade charges in second debate|first1=Ken|last1=Dixon|first2=Staff|last2=Writer|date=October 8, 2010|website=Connecticut Post}}</ref> During a debate on October 7, McMahon criticized his vote as a state Senator in 1989 for a $850 million tax increase. Blumenthal fired back, referencing her memo to Pat Patterson, saying that while he was a state Senator in 1989, \"she was tipping off the doctor who worked for her about a federal investigation, a criminal investigation.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Blumenthal-McMahon-trade-charges-in-2nd-debate-691441.php | title=Blumenthal, McMahon trade charges in second debate| date=October 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Scott Brown endorsement===\nOn October 9, Linda McMahon received the endorsement of Massachusetts U.S. Senator [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20101010/NWS01/310109815/-1/NWS |title=Scott Brown campaigns for McMahon |last=Mann |first=Ted |publisher=The Day (Connecticut) |date=October 10, 2010 |accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref> a Republican who had been elected to the Senate in a [[United States Senate special election in Massachusetts, 2010|January 2010 special election]] to the seat long-held by Democrat [[Ted Kennedy]]. The rally was held in front of [[Milford, Connecticut|Milford]] City Hall and was attended by around 250 people. Brown had also faced a once-favored Democratic state attorney general in his bid for U.S. Senate, [[Martha Coakley]].\n\n==Political positions==\nMcMahon campaigned on a platform of [[fiscal conservatism]], lower taxes, and job creation.<ref name=\"first100days\">{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/news/opinion/hc-mcmahon-senator-100-days.artfeb28,0,952366,print.story|title=Linda McMahon: My first 100 days|newspaper=Hartford Courant|author=Linda McMahon|date=February 28, 2010|accessdate=2010-03-09}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She opposed the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|2009 stimulus act]], saying the money from the stimulus \"went into government agencies, not the hands of small businesses that are going to create 70% of jobs.\"<ref name=\"Courant interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.courant.com/news/ctpolitics/hc-mcmahon-retrospect-1220.artdec20,0,985577,full.story |title=Linda McMahon Wrestling in New Ring: Politics |author=Daniela Altimari |publisher=Hartford Courant |date=2009-12-20 |accessdate=2010-01-17 |work=The Hartford Courant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928023022/http://www.courant.com/news/ctpolitics/hc-mcmahon-retrospect-1220.artdec20%2C0%2C985577%2Cfull.story |archivedate=September 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> McMahon also denounced [[deficit spending]], expressing support for a [[Balanced budget amendment|Constitutional balanced budget amendment]].<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linda2010.com/images/pdf/Linda_McMahon_Jobs_Plan.pdf |title=Jobs Plan PDF |accessdate=2010-06-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021210851/http://www.linda2010.com/images/pdf/Linda_McMahon_Jobs_Plan.pdf |archivedate=October 21, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linda2010.com/issues/fiscal-discipline/|title=Fiscal Discipline \u2013 Linda McMahon for Senate|accessdate=2010-03-08|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326134551/http://www.linda2010.com/issues/fiscal-discipline |archivedate=March 26, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> McMahon blamed [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democrats]] for not reclaiming unspent money from the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]] (TARP) and the bailout package, saying the money should be used to repay government debts.<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/><ref group=\"nb\">\nMcMahon gave an interview supporting TARP in its original form, which was to purchase toxic assets in the context of a financial crisis. Nevertheless, she has been a strong opponent of the TARP program throughout the campaign, saying that the government overstepped its authority in purchasing shares of the automobile and banking industries.\n*See [http://www.linda2010.com/news/2009/11/qa-linda-mcmahon-talks-west-hartford-politics/ West Hartford interview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227065343/http://www.linda2010.com/news/2009/11/qa-linda-mcmahon-talks-west-hartford-politics/ |date=December 27, 2010 }}\n*See [http://blogs.courant.com/rick_green/2009/12/mcmahon-ad-hands-simmons-a-con.html McMahon ad hands Simmons a conservative club, UPDATED] December 9, 2009</ref> She also accused the [[Executive Branch]] of evading the system of [[checks and balances]] through the use of \"[[czar (political term)#Criticism|policy czars]]\" and [[executive order (United States)|executive orders]].<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/>\n\nMcMahon attacked [[the Federal Reserve]] for \"[[micromanaging]]\" small banks through the stimulus programs and called for an end to bank bailouts.<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/> McMahon alleged that the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132010|U.S. financial crisis]] could be attributed in part to the repeal of the [[Glass\u2013Steagall Act]] in 1999, and advocated that Congress [[Glass\u2013Steagall Act#Proposed reenactment|revisit the issue]].<ref name=\"mcmahonlikesherchances\"/> She stated that small business creates most new jobs, and that government created many obstacles to economic recovery. She pushed for greater credit availability to help businesses invest.<ref name=\"mcmahonlikesherchances\"/>\n\nOn April 7, 2010, McMahon's campaign unveiled a jobs plan to \"put Connecticut back to work.\" The plan was modeled on [[Reaganomics]], crediting [[John Rutledge (economist)|Dr. John Rutledge]], who wrote many of Reagan's policies in 1980\u201381, as Chief Economic Adviser to the McMahon campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ameriborn.com/?p=2407 |title=Linda McMahon Releases Jobs Plan |publisher=Ameriborn.com |date=April 7, 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707130538/http://ameriborn.com/?p=2407 |archive-date=July 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Proposals in the plan included:\n<ref>{{cite web|author=Evan McMorris-Santoro |date= May 14, 2010<!--, 9:22&nbsp;am -->|url=http://tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com/2010/05/doh-linda-mcmahon-picks-now-to-call-for-more-offshore-drilling.php |title=D'oh! Linda McMahon Picks Now To Call For More Offshore Drilling &#124; TPMDC |publisher=Tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/05/14/linda-mcmahon-connecticut_n_576301.html |title=Linda McMahon, Connecticut Senate Contender: Now Is The Time To Promote Offshore Oil Drilling |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= May 14, 2010|accessdate=2010-08-14 |first=Jason |last=Linkins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jonathan Kantrowitz |url=http://blog.ctnews.com/kantrowitz/2010/05/15/linda-mcmahon-drill-baby-drill/ |title=Linda McMahon: Drill Baby, Drill \u2013 Jonathan Kantrowitz \u2013 Connecticut News |publisher=Blog.ctnews.com |date=May 15, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n* lower tax rates for [[capital gains tax in the United States|capital gains]] and [[dividend]]s\n* abolition of the [[estate tax]] and the [[gift tax in the United States|gift tax]]\n* greater tax deductions to encourage savings for [[Individual Retirement Account|IRAs]] and higher education\n* passage of pending free trade agreements with [[United States \u2013 Colombia Free Trade Agreement|Colombia]], [[Panama \u2013 United States Trade Promotion Agreement|Panama]], and [[South Korea \u2013 United States Free Trade Agreement|South Korea]]\n* government deregulation, rejecting [[cap and trade]] and [[card check]] legislation<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/>\n\nMcMahon supported [[offshore drilling]]. After the [[BP Oil Spill]], a McMahon spokesman said she desired stronger penalties for such incidents, but believed a moratorium on new drilling would devastate economies in [[Gulf of Mexico|Gulf]] states, and make America \"more dependent on foreign oil\".<ref name=\"drillingspeech\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtHAqY8n5Js&feature=player_embedded |title=McMahon Downplays \"Accidents\" Like BP Gulf Oil Spill, Argues for More Offshore Drilling |publisher=YouTube |date=May 24, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhregister.com/articles/2010/06/15/news/doc4c17c54a49dc6388223986.txt |title=Spill estimates grow; Blumenthal says rein in Big Oil- The New Haven Register \u2013 Serving New Haven, Connecticut |publisher=Nhregister.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> She supported expanded drilling, naming the [[Outer Continental Shelf]], [[ANWR]], the [[Green River Formation]], and the [[Bakken Formation|Bakken Shale Deposits]] as attractive sites for energy exploration.<ref name=\"Jobs Plan\"/> McMahon also supported alternative energy, including [[fuel cell|fuel-cell]], [[solar energy|solar]], [[wind energy|wind]] and [[geothermal energy|geothermal technology]].<ref name=\"mcmahonlikesherchances\">{{cite web |last=Benjamin |first=Scott |url=http://www.housatonictimes.com/articles/2010/04/23/news/political/doc4bd1a65533bee562586762.txt |title=McMahon Likes Her Chances \u2013 News |publisher=Housatonic Times |date=April 23, 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130125212157/http://www.housatonictimes.com/articles/2010/04/23/news/political/doc4bd1a65533bee562586762.txt |archivedate=January 25, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"drillingspeech\"/>\n\nMcMahon claimed to be socially moderate. She was [[pro-choice]], and donated to [[Republican Majority for Choice]]. She did not support [[partial birth abortions]] and favored [[parental notification]] laws.<ref name=\"Courant interview\"/> McMahon opposed amnesty for [[illegal immigrants]] and supported [[Mexico - United States border#Security|border security]]. She supported fixing the visa application process to encourage legal [[immigration]]. She generally supported [[gay rights]], including the repeal of [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell]]. She personally felt that marriage should be between a man and a woman, but favored [[states rights|state authority]] on the issue of [[same-sex marriage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b63HP13Lrkc |title=Linda McMahon on the View |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref> McMahon voiced displeasure with federal statutes on same-sex marriage, such as the [[Defense of Marriage Act]].<ref name=\"first returns\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/5215/mcmahons-investment-produces-its-first-returns |title=McMahon's investment produces its first returns &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=March 19, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref>\n\nOn [[United States foreign policy|foreign policy]], McMahon expressed interest in joining a defense-related [[United States congressional committee|committee in the Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/opinion/opedcolumnists/connecticut_is_ready_to_rumble_XC9xevF2Rr2t4HXkGThSiK#ixzz0wmiDXZWf|title=Connecticut is ready to rumble|author=Maureen Callahan|accessdate=2010-08-15 | work=New York Post | date=August 15, 2010}}</ref> Concerning the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]], McMahon said she was \"apprehensive about the economic repercussions of a protracted war\", but said \"It is my hope that we bring our troops home safely as soon as possible, but we should bring them home responsibly and in victory, not defeat.\"<ref name=\"Courant interview\"/> During a Republican debate, she took a \"hawkish\" stance on [[Iran]], saying all options should be on the table, including the military one.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstimes.com/news/article/GOP-Senate-candidates-spar-in-debate-388520.php |title=GOP Senate candidates spar in debate |publisher=NewsTimes |date=March 2, 2010 |accessdate=2010-06-03}}</ref> She said that the U.S. military should be \"second to none\", and promised more representation to [[defense contractors]] from Connecticut, including [[Sikorsky Aircraft|Sikorsky]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/08/16/connecticut-gop-candidates-seize-use-russian-choppers-afghanistan/ | work=Fox News | title=Connecticut GOP Candidates Seize on U.S. Use of Russian Choppers in Afghanistan | date=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Analysis==\n\n===Campaign scrutiny===\nThe McMahon campaign was criticized for providing only limited direct access to the candidate. McMahon was accompanied by political staff at all public events. She limited her press availability to scheduled one-on-one interviews, avoiding traditional press conferences and impromptu questions. Staff highly controlled her photo opportunities, Twitter postings, and public events, often not notifying the press of events in advance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Wrestling-s-steel-magnolia-McMahon-closes-in-on-607482.php |title=Wrestling's steel magnolia, McMahon closes in on GOP nod \u2013 Connecticut Post |publisher=Ctpost.com |date=August 7, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref name=\"press questioner\">{{cite web|last=Cole |first=Joseph |url=http://valley.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/linda_mcmahon_makes_her_case_in_seymour/ |title=Linda McMahon States Her Case in Seymour &#124; Valley Independent Sentinel |publisher=Valley.newhavenindependent.org |date=February 26, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bass |first=Paul |url=http://www.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/mcmahon_reality_checks_independent/ |title=McMahon \"Reality Checks\" Independent |publisher=New Haven Independent |date=March 2, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McClarin |first=Jim |url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/04/rob-simmons-linda-mcmahon-and.html |title=Rob Simmons, Linda McMahon and the Fourth Estate \u2013 Capitol Watch |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707013545/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/04/rob-simmons-linda-mcmahon-and.html |archivedate=July 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yourct.com/2010/03/linda-mcmahon/ |title=Linda McMahon |publisher=YourCT.com |date=March 6, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718143523/http://www.yourct.com/2010/03/linda-mcmahon/ |archive-date=July 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nMcMahon did not discuss the topic of federal programs such as [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], [[Medicaid]] and [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] in the weeks before the Republican primary, leading to accusations she was avoiding controversial issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/7074/mcmahon-promises-change-while-avoiding-controversy |title=McMahon promises change, avoids controversy on difficult issues &#124; The Connecticut Mirror |publisher=Ctmirror.org |date=August 2, 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812032258/http://www.ctmirror.org/story/7074/mcmahon-promises-change-while-avoiding-controversy |archivedate=August 12, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \"She claims she wants to cut federal spending, yet refuses to discuss her position on Medicare and Social Security, two of the most costly entitlement programs.\"<ref name=\"theatlanticwire.com\"/>\n\n===McMahon family campaign presence===\n[[Image:Mrmcmahon092407.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Vince McMahon did not appear on the campaign trail with Linda for much of her campaign.]]\nMcMahon's husband, Vince McMahon, did not actively campaign for his spouse, causing some to wonder if Linda was purposely distancing herself from him.<!-- who?--><ref>Vigdor, Neil. (March 26, 2010) [http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Paging-Vince-McMahon-Flamboyant-WWE-showman-424644.php#page-1 Paging Vince McMahon: Flamboyant WWE showman keeps a low profile during wife's Senate run ] Stamford Advocate. Retrieved 2010-03-29.</ref> In February 2010, Linda said Vince was too busy \"running the company\" as both chairman and [[CEO]] to campaign, but said he may be involved \"down the road\".<ref>Kate Snow, David Muir. ABC News Transcript. (January 9, 2010) \"Senate Smackdown: Former Female CEO Running for Office.\" Televised on ABC World News Saturday. Waterbury, Connecticut. Retrieved 2010-02-06.</ref> Several speculators predicted that if he campaigned with her, his direct association with controversial wrestling skits would be a \"major liability\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2009/09/will-wwe-chair-vince-mcmahon-hurt-lindas-senate-hopes/|title=Will WWE Chair Vince McMahon Hurt Linda's Senate Hopes?|first=Ben|last=Buchwalter}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon's son-in-law, WWE wrestler [[Triple H]], gave an interview<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VNFubVuFcJ4|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref> to the ''Wall Street Journal'' on March 12, 2010, where he said he had purposely kept an \"arms length away from Linda\" during her campaign to avoid giving her bad publicity. On March 14, 2010, a news story in the ''Stamford Advocate'' revealed that her husband, Vince McMahon, owned a 47-foot sports yacht called ''The Sexy Bitch''.<ref>[http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/The-running-of-the-rich-Is-wealth-changing-406355.php#page-1 The running of the rich: Is wealth changing Connecticut politics?]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/article/vince-mcmahon-earns-linda-mcmahon-some-bad-press-98123 |title=Wrestlezone article \u2013 Vince McMahon earns Linda McMahon some bad press |access-date=June 3, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322194906/http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/article/vince-mcmahon-earns-linda-mcmahon-some-bad-press-98123 |archive-date=March 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>Collins, David. (March 19, 2010) [http://www.theday.com/article/20100319/NWS05/303199849/-1/NWS Linda McMahon's yacht is named what?! '''The Day''' Accessed 2010-03-19.]</ref> Linda's absence from the wrestling industry was also noted on April 20, when an article by the ''[[Greenwich Time (newspaper)|Greenwich Time]]'' reported that she was courting voters in [[Westport, Connecticut]] while her husband was running a live wrestling event at the [[Mohegan Sun Arena]].<ref>[http://www.greenwichtime.com/local/article/Originally-in-Sunday-s-paper-SmackDown-comes-463405.php Originally in Sunday's paper: 'SmackDown' comes to Connecticut as Linda McMahon keeps a distance]</ref>\n\nVince McMahon appeared together with Linda for the first time on April 21, 2010, at a charity function at [[Sacred Heart University]]. At one point during the event, he reportedly grabbed a microphone and said to Richard Blumenthal:\n{{quote|My name is Vince McMahon and my wife is the one who's going to beat you this fall.<ref>{{cite web |last=McCrackin |first=Phil |url=http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/04/vince-mcmahon-to-dick-blumenth.html |title=Vince McMahon to Dick Blumenthal: My wife will whoop you \u2013 Capitol Watch |publisher=Blogs.courant.com |accessdate=2010-08-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120708043425/http://blogs.courant.com/capitol_watch/2010/04/vince-mcmahon-to-dick-blumenth.html |archivedate=July 8, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= lordsofpain.net| url=http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/wwe/7526.html |accessdate=June 3, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501230047/http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/wwe/7526.html |archivedate=May 1, 2010 }}</ref>}}\n\n====Vince McMahon's activities====\nThrough October and November 2010, Vince McMahon took increasing action to support fans and the company image which he believed was being damaged by Linda's campaign. On several occasions, [[Connecticut Secretary of State]] [[Susan Bysiewicz]] stated that poll workers had the right to bar voters wearing WWE merchandise to the polls, claiming they were \"political items\". WWE filed a federal lawsuit against Bysiewicz to prevent this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/breaking-news/hc-xpm-2010-10-26-hc-vince-mcmahon-lawsuit-1026-story.html|title=A Defiant Vince McMahon Has Filed A Lawsuit Against Susan Bysiewicz|first=DANIELA|last=ALTIMARI|website=courant.com}}</ref> He also launched a \"Stand up for WWE\" campaign on the Internet and gave away company T-shirts and merchandise.\n\nOn October 30, 2010, WWE held a \"Fan Appreciation Day\" in Hartford, Connecticut. Vince acknowledged that the event was held to counter the negative publicity from the Senate race.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.newstimes.com/default/article/Democrats-file-elections-complaint-against-World-714956.php |title = Democrats accuse McMahon of improperly using WWE resources|date = October 21, 2010}}</ref> During the wrestling show, McMahon distanced himself from his wife's political campaign, saying, \"Some people may think I was going to talk about politics today. Nothing could be further from the truth. I do encourage you to vote this Tuesday, and while you're voting, feel free to wear a WWE T-shirt. I came out here to simply say thank you. That's what this day is all about. It's about fan appreciation. No one appreciates the fans more than World Wrestling Entertainment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20101030/NWS12/101039984|title=Wrestling for votes? Nope. Just wrestling|website=The Day}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2010-10-30-hc-gop-campaigning-1031-20101030-story.html|title=WWE Fans Urged To Vote|first=CHRISTOPHER|last=KEATING|website=courant.com}}</ref> The Connecticut Democratic Party filed an FEC complaint against Linda McMahon's campaign in October, claiming the WWE's \"Fan Appreciation Day\" was an \"illegal campaign contribution\". The complaint also cited the taping of \"Smackdown in Bridgeport Harbor Yard\" on [[Election Day (United States)|Election Day]], claiming it intended to suppress voter turnout in a Democratic-leaning community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/stories/1010/43899.html|title=Dems want FEC slam on McMahon|first=Jake|last=Sherman|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\n===2012 candidacy===\n\nMcMahon ran in the [[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2012]], and lost to [[Chris Murphy (Connecticut politician)|Chris Murphy]].\n\n==Results==\n{{Election box begin \n| title = United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statementofvote-sots.ct.gov/StatementOfVote/WebModules/ReportsLink/USSenTownView.aspx?Parameter=11/02/2010-General |title=Statement of Vote: Election Results for United States Senator Summarized by Town |publisher=The State of Connecticut Secretary of the State |accessdate=December 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101122180406/http://www.statementofvote-sots.ct.gov/StatementOfVote/WebModules/ReportsLink/USSenTownView.aspx?Parameter=11%2F02%2F2010-General |archivedate=November 22, 2010 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n| candidate = Richard Blumenthal\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 636,040\n| percentage = 55.16%\n| change = -11.20%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = Linda E. McMahon\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 498,341\n| percentage = 43.22%\n| change = +11.08%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = Warren B. Mosler\n| party = Independent (politician)\n| votes = 11,275\n| percentage = 0.98%\n| change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = Dr. John Mertens\n| party = Connecticut for Lieberman\n| votes = 6,735\n| percentage = 0.58%\n| change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = Write-in candidates (8)\n| party = Write-in candidate\n| votes = 724\n| percentage = 0.06%\n| change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  |votes      = 137,755\n  |percentage = 11.95%\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box total\n| votes = 1,153,115\n| percentage = 100\n| change =\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no swing\n  |winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |loser = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2010]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart=126623 | fec=S0CT00151 | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Linda_McMahon.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/person/9269027 Appearances] on [[C-SPAN]] programs\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/linda_e_mcmahon/index.html Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/gIQAPjsz6O_topic.html Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* -->\n*[http://www.opensecrets.org/races/summary.php?cycle=2010&id=CTS2 Campaign contributions] at [[OpenSecrets.org]]\n\n{{United States elections, 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linda Mcmahon U.S. Senate Campaign, 2010}}\n[[Category:2010 United States Senate elections]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "names of newspapers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_Linda_McMahon_U.S._Senate_campaign"}
{"title_page": "Janggi", "text_new": "{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Korean words and phrases]]}}\n{{Infobox game\n| italic title = no\n| title = ''Janggi''\n| image = Janggi.svg\n| image_size = 280px\n| image_caption = ''Janggi'' board and starting setup\n| years = \n| genre = [[Board game]] <br />[[Abstract strategy game]] <br />[[Mind sport]]\n| players = 2\n| setup_time = < 1 minute\n| playing_time = From 20 minutes to several hours\n| random_chance = None\n| skills = [[Strategy game|Strategy]], tactics \n| AKA = Changgi <br />Janki <br />Korean chess \n| footnotes =\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul=\uc7a5\uae30\n|hanja=\u5c07\u68cb\n|rr=janggi\n|mr=changgi\n}}\n\n'''''Janggi''''' (including romanizations ''changgi'' and ''jangki''), sometimes called '''Korean chess''', is a [[Abstract strategy game|strategy]] [[board game]] popular in Korea. The game derived from [[xiangqi]] (Chinese chess) and is very similar to it, including the starting position of the pieces, and the 9\u00d710 gameboard, but without the xiangqi \"river\" dividing the board horizontally in the middle.\n\nJanggi is played on a board nine lines wide by ten lines long. The game is sometimes fast paced due to the jumping cannons and the long-range elephants, but professional games most often last over 150 moves and so are typically slower than those of [[Chess|Western chess]].\n\nIn 2009, the first world janggi tournament was held in [[Harbin]], [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.873k.com/?mid=News_TPYX&page=2&document_srl=70014|title=<span lang=\"ko\">\uc81c1\ud68c \uc138\uacc4\uc778\uc7a5\uae30\ub300\ud68c \ud560\ube48\uc11c \uc131\ud669\ub9ac\uc5d0</span>|language=Korean|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721011856/http://www.873k.com/?mid=News_TPYX&page=2&document_srl=70014 |archive-date=2011-07-21 }}</ref>\n\n==Rules==\n\n===Board===\nThe board is composed of 90 intersections of 9 vertical files and 10 horizontal rows. The board has nearly the same layout as that used in [[xiangqi]], except the janggi board has no \"river\" in the central row. The pieces consist of disks marked with identifying characters and are placed on the line intersections (as in [[xiangqi]] and [[Go (board game)|Go]]). Janggi pieces are traditionally [[octagon]]al in shape, and differ in size according to their rank. The sides are Blue (or sometimes Green), which moves first, versus Red. Each side has a ''palace'' that is 3 lines by 3 lines (9 positions) in the centre of their side of the board against the back edge. The palace contains four diagonal lines extending outwards from the centre, forming an \"X\" shape.\n\n===Pieces===\nThe pieces are labeled with [[hanja]] (Chinese characters). The labels on the blue pieces are all written in the [[semi-cursive script]]. For instance, the blue chariot or ''cha'' has a cursive version of {{lang|ko-Hant|\u8eca}}, which looks something like {{lang|zh-Hans|\u8f66}} (the [[Simplified Chinese character|Simplified Chinese]] equivalent of the [[Traditional Chinese character|traditional character]]).\n\n====General====\n[[Image: Red King (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green King (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThe pieces that are equivalent to the [[King (chess)|kings]] in Western chess are actually referred to as military generals (''janggun'') in Korean. They are labelled with the [[Chinese character]] ''Han'' (in Chinese [[pinyin]]: ''H\u00e0n''; {{lang|ko-Hant|\u6f22}}) on the red side, and ''Cho'' (''Ch\u01d4''; {{lang|ko-Hant|\u695a}}) on the blue side. They represent the rival states of [[Han (state)|Han]] and [[Chu (state)|Chu]] that fought for power in the post-[[Qin Dynasty]] interregnum period in China (see [[Chu\u2013Han contention]]). In North Korea, the Chu\u2013Han setup is not used; the red general there is called ''jang'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5c07}}, \"general\") and the blue general is called ''gwan'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5b98}}, \"minister\").  Both kings can also be referred to generally as ''gung'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5bae}}, \"palace\").<ref>[[:ko:\uc7a5\uae30#.EC.83.B9.EC.B9.98.EC.99.80.EC.9D.98 .EC.B0.A8.EC.9D.B4.EC.A0.90]]</ref>\n\nJanggi differs from its [[xiangqi|Chinese counterpart]] in that the janggi general starts the game from the central intersection of the palace, rather than from the centre intersection of the back edge. The general may move one step per turn along marked board lines to any of the nine points within the palace. There are four diagonal lines in the palace connecting the centre position to the corners. When the general is checkmated the game is lost. The general cannot leave the palace under any circumstances. If the generals come to face each other across the board, and the player to move does not move away, this is ''bikjang''\u2014a draw. This rule is different from that of [[xiangqi]] where it is illegal for the generals to face.\n\nIf there is no move for the general to make without getting into check or checkmate, but it is safe for it to stand still, the person may pass their turn (leave the general in position and make no move).\n\n====Guards====\n[[Image: Red Sa (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Sa (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThe pieces are labeled ''sa'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u58eb}}) and are civilian government officials (i.e. council members serving the commander in chief). They are often called guards, since they stay close to the general. Other names are assistants or mandarins.\n\nThe guards start to the left and right of the general on the first rank. They move the same as the general, one step per turn along marked lines in the palace. The guards are one of the weakest pieces because they may not leave the palace. They are valuable for protecting the general.\n\n====Horses====\n[[Image: Red Ma (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Ma (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nCalled the horse or ''ma'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u99ac}}), this piece moves and captures exactly like the [[Xiangqi#Horse|horse in xiangqi]] (i.e. one step orthogonally then one step diagonally outward, with no jumping). A horse can be transposed with an adjacent elephant in the initial setup.\n\n====Elephants====\n[[Image: Red Sang (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Sang (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThe elephants or ''sang'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u8c61}}) begin the game to the left and right of the guards. They move one point orthogonally followed by two points diagonally away from their starting point, ending on the opposite corner of a 2\u00d73 rectangle. Like the horse, the elephant is blocked from moving by any intervening pieces. Unlike [[xiangqi]], which confines elephants to their own side of the board behind a \"river\", in janggi there is no river and  elephants are not limited to one side of the board. The janggi elephant can therefore be used more offensively than the xiangqi elephant. An elephant can be transposed with an adjacent horse in the initial setup.\n\n====Chariots====\n[[Image: Red Cha (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Cha (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThese are labelled ''cha'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u8eca}}). Like the [[Rook (chess)|rook]] in Western chess, the chariot moves and captures in a straight line either horizontally or vertically. Additionally, the chariot may move along the diagonal lines inside either palace, but only in a straight line. The two chariots begin the game in the corners. The chariot is the most powerful piece in the game.\n\n====Cannons====\n[[Image: Red Po (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Po (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThese are labelled ''po'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5305}}). Each player has two cannons. The cannons are placed on the row behind the soldiers, directly in front of the horses (if the horses are put on the file next to the chariots). The cannon moves by jumping another piece horizontally or vertically. The jump can be performed over any distance provided that there is exactly one piece anywhere between the original position and the target. In order to capture a piece, there must be exactly one piece (friendly or otherwise) between the cannon and the piece to be captured. The cannon then moves to that point and captures the piece. They may also move or capture diagonally along the diagonal lines in either palace, provided there is an intervening piece in the centre (i.e. it can only happen if the cannon is at a corner of the palace) They are powerful at the beginning of the game when \"hurdles\" are plentiful, but lose value rapidly with attrition. The other piece over which the cannon jumps may not be another cannon. A cannon may also not capture another cannon. Unlike [[xiangqi]], janggi requires cannons to jump in order to move, as well as capture. This means in the starting position, there are no valid moves available for the cannon.\n\n====Soldiers====\n[[Image: Red Byung (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Zol (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThese are labelled ''byeong'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5175}}) (soldiers, general term for a soldier) for Red and ''jol'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5352}}) (also means soldiers, usually lowest ranking soldiers) for Blue. Each side has five soldiers, initially placed on alternating points, one row back from the edge of where the river would be in xiangqi. Unlike [[Pawn (chess)|pawns]] in Western chess, they move and capture one point either straight forward or sideways. (Unlike xiangqi, where soldiers must be promoted to move sideways.) There is no promotion; once they reach the end of the board they may only move sideways. Soldiers may also move one point diagonally forward when within the enemy palace.\n\n===Setting up===\nIn tournaments, the elder player, or higher ranked player, conceals a soldier from each side in their hands. The opponent selects a hand to determine their colour. After that, Han places their pieces first, followed by Cho placing theirs. (The reason both sides are not placed simultaneously is because the positions of horse and elephant can be transposed, giving some strategical advantage to the player who places last.)\n\nAfter the pieces are set up, Cho moves first.\n\n===Ending the game===\nThe game is won by [[Checkmate|checkmating]] the opposing general. This is called ''oetong'' ({{lang|ko|\uc678\ud1b5}}).\n\nIn Western chess, [[stalemate]] is achieved when no legal moves are possible. However, the stalemate is not a draw in janggi. The player must pass their turn when no legal moves are possible. If neither player can move legally, or if neither player can win because neither player has enough pieces, the game ends in a draw.\n\nA player may decide to make a move such that their general faces the opponent's general unobstructed (a condition called ''bikjang''). In this situation, the opponent can either call a draw, or make a move that breaks the condition. In many cases, the bikjang rule can be used to force the opponent to call a draw on a losing game, by forcing them to sacrifice a valuable piece to break the bikjang position. It may not apply in some games, and usually the players will consent on the validity of the rule before the game begins.\n\nCheck is announced by declaring ''janggun'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5c07\u8ecd}}), meaning \"general\". Getting out of janggun is called meonggun, and one may declare ''meonggun'' while escaping from janggun. But it is not necessary to say ''janggun'' out loud.\n\n===Miscellaneous rules===\nIn South Korean tournaments, according to rules set by the Korean Janggi Association,<ref>http://www.kja.or.kr/</ref> there is no draw in any form, including draw by perpetual check or repetition of position. If a position repeats three times, a referee is called to determine who is at fault. Usually the referee orders the player who is losing to make a different move, so the player who is winning can press for an advantage. Sometimes it is not technically clear who is to blame, and different referees may differ as to which player must deviate, or whether repetition is mutually forced. This rule is applied because a winner and a loser must be decided during the game. If both players have less than 30 piece points, however, a draw is allowed by both repetition and perpetual check.\n\nIn tournaments where draws are not allowed, draws are resolved by adding up the points of their pieces that are still on the board.\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable\"\n ! Piece !! Points\n |-\n | chariots || align=\"center\" | 13\n |-\n | cannons || align=\"center\" | 7\n |-\n | horses || align=\"center\" | 5\n |-\n | elephants || align=\"center\" | 3\n |-\n | guards || align=\"center\" | 3\n |-\n | soldiers || align=\"center\" | 2\n|}\n\nBecause the player with the blue pieces (''cho'') starts, they have an advantage. To compensate for this, Red receives 1.5 points (called 'deom' (\ub364) in Korean), the half-point being to avoid ties. So when the game starts, Blue has 72 points and Red has 73.5 points. If neither side can force a win, the player with the most points is declared the winner.\n\n==In South Korean culture==\n[[Image:Janggi-seoul.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|Playing janggi on [[Seoul]]'s streets]]\nIn South Korea one will often see older men crowding around a single janggi board while two men play for small amounts of money.  These games are played year round, especially in city parks in [[Seoul]].  Janggi is occasionally played as a gambling game, and it is currently less popular in South Korea than the [[strategy game]] baduk (known in the West as [[Go (board game)|go]]).\n\nThe [[Korea Janggi Association]] is responsible for promoting janggi in South Korea.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Gwangsanghui]] (\u5ee3\u8c61\u6231, \uad11\uc0c1\ud76c)\u2014an 18th-century Janggi variant<ref name=\"\u97e9\u56fd\u53e4\u5178\u7efc\u5408\u6570\u636e\u5e93 \u300a\u4a13\u6df5\u96c6\u00b7\u5ee3\u8c61\u6231\u5fd7\u300b\">{{cite web|url=http://db.itkc.or.kr/index.jsp?bizName=MM&url=/itkcdb/text/nodeViewIframe.jsp?bizName=MM&seojiId=kc_mm_a513&gunchaId=av027&muncheId=01&finId=021&NodeId=&setid=2526027&Pos=0&TotalCount=11&searchUrl=ok|title=<span lang=\"zh\">\u97e9\u56fd\u53e4\u5178\u7efc\u5408\u6570\u636e\u5e93 \u300a\u4a13\u6df5\u96c6\u00b7\u5ee3\u8c61\u6231\u5fd7\u300b</span>|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130423124005/http://db.itkc.or.kr/index.jsp?bizName=MM&url=/itkcdb/text/nodeViewIframe.jsp%3FbizName=MM&seojiId=kc_mm_a513&gunchaId=av027&muncheId=01&finId=021&NodeId=&setid=2526027&Pos=0&TotalCount=11&searchUrl=ok |archive-date=2013-04-23 }}</ref>\n*[[List of Korea-related topics]]\n*[[Xiangqi]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite magazine\n |last=Maynard\n |first=Malcolm\n |title=Janggi: The Chess of Korea\n |editor=Kerry Handscomb\n |publisher=Carpe Diem Publishing\n |magazine=Abstract Games\n |date=Winter 2002\n |issue=12\n |pages=6\u201311\n |issn=1492-0492}}\n*{{cite magazine\n |last=Maynard\n |first=Malcolm\n |title=Janggi: Addenda\n |editor=Kerry Handscomb\n |publisher=Carpe Diem Publishing\n |magazine=Abstract Games\n |date=Autumn 2003\n |issue=15\n |page=28\n |issn=1492-0492}}\n*{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=H. J. R.\n |authorlink=H. J. R. Murray\n |title=[[A History of Chess]]\n |edition=Reissued\n |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]\n |year=1913\n |pages=134\u201337\n |isbn=0-19-827403-3}}\n*{{cite book\n |last=Pritchard \n |first=D. B. \n |authorlink=David Pritchard (chess player)\n |title=The Encyclopedia of Chess Variants\n |publisher=Games & Puzzles Publications\n |year=1994\n |pages=164\u201365\n |isbn=0-9524142-0-1}}\n*{{cite book\n |last=Pritchard \n |first=D. B. \n |authorlink=David Pritchard (chess player)\n |editor-last=Beasley\n |editor-first=John\n |title=The Classified Encyclopedia of Chess Variants\n |publisher=John Beasley \n |year=2007\n |pages=250\u201351\n |isbn=978-0-9555168-0-1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Janggi}}\n* [http://history.chess.free.fr/changgi.htm \"Janggi, the Korean Chess\"] by Jean-Louis Cazaux; presentation, rules, history\n* [http://www.chessvariants.org/oriental.dir/koreanchess.html Janggi: Korean Chess] by Jean-Louis Cazaux, ''[[The Chess Variant Pages]]'' \n* [http://www.kja.or.kr/ Korea Janggi Association] {{in lang|ko}}\n*{{cite web |url= http://home.att.net/~Mc-Kiernan/XiangQi/XiangQi.pdf |title= Essentials of Chinese Chess and of Korean Chess |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070614111608/http://home.att.net/~Mc-Kiernan/XiangQi/XiangQi.pdf |archivedate= 2007-06-14 }}&nbsp;{{small|(217&nbsp;[[Kibibyte|KiB]])}}\n* [http://www.smashwords.com/books/view/179829 ''Introduction to Korean Chess''] by Chris McDade\n* [http://www.braintv.co.kr/ Brain TV] a janggi cable TV channel {{in lang|ko}}\n*{{bgg|5400|Changgi}}\n\n'''Playsites'''\n* [http://goldtoken.com/games/play?rules=XiangqiJ GoldToken.com]\n* [http://www.fungame.pe.kr/javagame/janggi/janggi.htm Janggi applet]\n* [http://www.pathguy.com/chess/KoreanCh.htm Korean Chess] a simple program by Ed Friedlander <span style=\"font-size:0.95em; font-weight:bold;\">([[Java (programming language)|Java]])</span>\n* [http://www.koreanchess.co.kr Online Janggi Board] a web Janggi board written in JavaScript\n\n{{Chess variants|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Janggi| ]]\n[[Category:Abstract strategy games]]\n[[Category:Games related to chaturanga]]\n[[Category:Traditional board games]]\n[[Category:Korean games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Korean words and phrases]]}}\n{{Infobox game\n| italic title = no\n| title = ''Janggi''\n| image = Janggi.svg\n| image_size = 280px\n| image_caption = ''Janggi'' board and starting setup\n| years = \n| genre = [[Board game]] <br />[[Abstract strategy game]] <br />[[Mind sport]]\n| players = 2\n| setup_time = < 1 minute\n| playing_time = From 20 minutes to several hours\n| random_chance = None\n| skills = [[Strategy game|Strategy]], tactics \n| AKA = Changgi <br />Janki <br />Korean chess \n| footnotes =\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul=\uc7a5\uae30\n|hanja=\u5c07\u68cb\n|rr=janggi\n|mr=changgi\n}}\n\n'''''Janggi''''' (including romanizations ''changgi'' and ''jangki''), sometimes called '''Korean chess''', is a [[Abstract strategy game|strategy]] [[board game]] popular in Korea. The game derived from [[xiangqi]] (Chinese chess) and is very similar to it, including the starting position of the pieces, and the 9\u00d710 gameboard, but without the xiangqi \"river\" dividing the board horizontally in the middle.\n\nJanggi is played on a board nine lines wide by ten lines long. The game is sometimes fast paced due to the jumping cannons and the long-range elephants, but professional games most often last over 150 moves and so are typically slower than those of [[Chess|Western chess]].\n\nIn 2009, the first world janggi tournament was held in [[Harbin]], [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.873k.com/?mid=News_TPYX&page=2&document_srl=70014|title=<span lang=\"ko\">\uc81c1\ud68c \uc138\uacc4\uc778\uc7a5\uae30\ub300\ud68c \ud560\ube48\uc11c \uc131\ud669\ub9ac\uc5d0</span>|language=Korean|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721011856/http://www.873k.com/?mid=News_TPYX&page=2&document_srl=70014 |archive-date=2011-07-21 }}</ref>\n\n==Rules==\n\n===Board===\nThe board is composed of 90 intersections of 9 vertical files and 10 horizontal rows. The board has nearly the same layout as that used in [[xiangqi]], except the janggi board has no \"river\" in the central row. The pieces consist of disks marked with identifying characters and are placed on the line intersections (as in [[xiangqi]] and [[Go (board game)|Go]]). Janggi pieces are traditionally [[octagon]]al in shape, and differ in size according to their rank. The sides are Blue (or sometimes Green), which moves first, versus Red. Each side has a ''palace'' that is 3 lines by 3 lines (9 positions) in the centre of their side of the board against the back edge. The palace contains four diagonal lines extending outwards from the centre, forming an \"X\" shape.\n\n===Pieces===\nThe pieces are labeled with [[hanja]] (Chinese characters). The labels on the blue pieces are all written in the [[semi-cursive script]]. For instance, the blue chariot or ''cha'' has a cursive version of {{lang|ko-Hant|\u8eca}}, which looks something like {{lang|zh-Hans|\u8f66}} (the [[Simplified Chinese character|Simplified Chinese]] equivalent of the [[Traditional Chinese character|traditional character]]).\n\n====General====\n[[Image: Red King (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green King (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThe pieces that are equivalent to the [[King (chess)|kings]] in Western chess are actually referred to as military generals (''janggun'') in Korean. They are labelled with the [[Chinese character]] ''Han'' (in Chinese [[pinyin]]: ''H\u00e0n''; {{lang|ko-Hant|\u6f22}}) on the red side, and ''Cho'' (''Ch\u01d4''; {{lang|ko-Hant|\u695a}}) on the blue side. They represent the rival states of [[Han (state)|Han]] and [[Chu (state)|Chu]] that fought for power in the post-[[Qin Dynasty]] interregnum period in China (see [[Chu\u2013Han contention]]). In North Korea, the Chu\u2013Han setup is not used; the red general there is called ''jang'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5c07}}, \"general\") and the blue general is called ''gwan'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5b98}}, \"minister\").  Both kings can also be referred to generally as''gung'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5bae}}, \"palace\").<ref>[[:ko:\uc7a5\uae30#.EC.83.B9.EC.B9.98.EC.99.80.EC.9D.98 .EC.B0.A8.EC.9D.B4.EC.A0.90]]</ref>\n\nJanggi differs from its [[xiangqi|Chinese counterpart]] in that the janggi general starts the game from the central intersection of the palace, rather than from the centre intersection of the back edge. The general may move one step per turn along marked board lines to any of the nine points within the palace. There are four diagonal lines in the palace connecting the centre position to the corners. When the general is checkmated the game is lost. The general cannot leave the palace under any circumstances. If the generals come to face each other across the board, and the player to move does not move away, this is ''bikjang''\u2014a draw. This rule is different from that of [[xiangqi]] where it is illegal for the generals to face.\n\nIf there is no move for the general to make without getting into check or checkmate, but it is safe for it to stand still, the person may pass their turn (leave the general in position and make no move).\n\n====Guards====\n[[Image: Red Sa (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Sa (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThe pieces are labeled ''sa'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u58eb}}) and are civilian government officials (i.e. council members serving the commander in chief). They are often called guards, since they stay close to the general. Other names are assistants or mandarins.\n\nThe guards start to the left and right of the general on the first rank. They move the same as the general, one step per turn along marked lines in the palace. The guards are one of the weakest pieces because they may not leave the palace. They are valuable for protecting the general.\n\n====Horses====\n[[Image: Red Ma (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Ma (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nCalled the horse or ''ma'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u99ac}}), this piece moves and captures exactly like the [[Xiangqi#Horse|horse in xiangqi]] (i.e. one step orthogonally then one step diagonally outward, with no jumping). A horse can be transposed with an adjacent elephant in the initial setup.\n\n====Elephants====\n[[Image: Red Sang (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Sang (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThe elephants or ''sang'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u8c61}}) begin the game to the left and right of the guards. They move one point orthogonally followed by two points diagonally away from their starting point, ending on the opposite corner of a 2\u00d73 rectangle. Like the horse, the elephant is blocked from moving by any intervening pieces. Unlike [[xiangqi]], which confines elephants to their own side of the board behind a \"river\", in janggi there is no river and  elephants are not limited to one side of the board. The janggi elephant can therefore be used more offensively than the xiangqi elephant. An elephant can be transposed with an adjacent horse in the initial setup.\n\n====Chariots====\n[[Image: Red Cha (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Cha (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThese are labelled ''cha'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u8eca}}). Like the [[Rook (chess)|rook]] in Western chess, the chariot moves and captures in a straight line either horizontally or vertically. Additionally, the chariot may move along the diagonal lines inside either palace, but only in a straight line. The two chariots begin the game in the corners. The chariot is the most powerful piece in the game.\n\n====Cannons====\n[[Image: Red Po (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Po (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThese are labelled ''po'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5305}}). Each player has two cannons. The cannons are placed on the row behind the soldiers, directly in front of the horses (if the horses are put on the file next to the chariots). The cannon moves by jumping another piece horizontally or vertically. The jump can be performed over any distance provided that there is exactly one piece anywhere between the original position and the target. In order to capture a piece, there must be exactly one piece (friendly or otherwise) between the cannon and the piece to be captured. The cannon then moves to that point and captures the piece. They may also move or capture diagonally along the diagonal lines in either palace, provided there is an intervening piece in the centre (i.e. it can only happen if the cannon is at a corner of the palace) They are powerful at the beginning of the game when \"hurdles\" are plentiful, but lose value rapidly with attrition. The other piece over which the cannon jumps may not be another cannon. A cannon may also not capture another cannon. Unlike [[xiangqi]], janggi requires cannons to jump in order to move, as well as capture. This means in the starting position, there are no valid moves available for the cannon.\n\n====Soldiers====\n[[Image: Red Byung (svg).svg|50px]]\n[[Image: Green Zol (svg).svg|50px]]\n\nThese are labelled ''byeong'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5175}}) (soldiers, general term for a soldier) for Red and ''jol'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5352}}) (also means soldiers, usually lowest ranking soldiers) for Blue. Each side has five soldiers, initially placed on alternating points, one row back from the edge of where the river would be in xiangqi. Unlike [[Pawn (chess)|pawns]] in Western chess, they move and capture one point either straight forward or sideways. (Unlike xiangqi, where soldiers must be promoted to move sideways.) There is no promotion; once they reach the end of the board they may only move sideways. Soldiers may also move one point diagonally forward when within the enemy palace.\n\n===Setting up===\nIn tournaments, the elder player, or higher ranked player, conceals a soldier from each side in their hands. The opponent selects a hand to determine their colour. After that, Han places their pieces first, followed by Cho placing theirs. (The reason both sides are not placed simultaneously is because the positions of horse and elephant can be transposed, giving some strategical advantage to the player who places last.)\n\nAfter the pieces are set up, Cho moves first.\n\n===Ending the game===\nThe game is won by [[Checkmate|checkmating]] the opposing general. This is called ''oetong'' ({{lang|ko|\uc678\ud1b5}}).\n\nIn Western chess, [[stalemate]] is achieved when no legal moves are possible. However, the stalemate is not a draw in janggi. The player must pass their turn when no legal moves are possible. If neither player can move legally, or if neither player can win because neither player has enough pieces, the game ends in a draw.\n\nA player may decide to make a move such that their general faces the opponent's general unobstructed (a condition called ''bikjang''). In this situation, the opponent can either call a draw, or make a move that breaks the condition. In many cases, the bikjang rule can be used to force the opponent to call a draw on a losing game, by forcing them to sacrifice a valuable piece to break the bikjang position. It may not apply in some games, and usually the players will consent on the validity of the rule before the game begins.\n\nCheck is announced by declaring ''janggun'' ({{lang|ko-Hant|\u5c07\u8ecd}}), meaning \"general\". Getting out of janggun is called meonggun, and one may declare ''meonggun'' while escaping from janggun. But it is not necessary to say ''janggun'' out loud.\n\n===Miscellaneous rules===\nIn South Korean tournaments, according to rules set by the Korean Janggi Association,<ref>http://www.kja.or.kr/</ref> there is no draw in any form, including draw by perpetual check or repetition of position. If a position repeats three times, a referee is called to determine who is at fault. Usually the referee orders the player who is losing to make a different move, so the player who is winning can press for an advantage. Sometimes it is not technically clear who is to blame, and different referees may differ as to which player must deviate, or whether repetition is mutually forced. This rule is applied because a winner and a loser must be decided during the game. If both players have less than 30 piece points, however, a draw is allowed by both repetition and perpetual check.\n\nIn tournaments where draws are not allowed, draws are resolved by adding up the points of their pieces that are still on the board.\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable\"\n ! Piece !! Points\n |-\n | chariots || align=\"center\" | 13\n |-\n | cannons || align=\"center\" | 7\n |-\n | horses || align=\"center\" | 5\n |-\n | elephants || align=\"center\" | 3\n |-\n | guards || align=\"center\" | 3\n |-\n | soldiers || align=\"center\" | 2\n|}\n\nBecause the player with the blue pieces (''cho'') starts, they have an advantage. To compensate for this, Red receives 1.5 points (called 'deom' (\ub364) in Korean), the half-point being to avoid ties. So when the game starts, Blue has 72 points and Red has 73.5 points. If neither side can force a win, the player with the most points is declared the winner.\n\n==In South Korean culture==\n[[Image:Janggi-seoul.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|Playing janggi on [[Seoul]]'s streets]]\nIn South Korea one will often see older men crowding around a single janggi board while two men play for small amounts of money.  These games are played year round, especially in city parks in [[Seoul]].  Janggi is occasionally played as a gambling game, and it is currently less popular in South Korea than the [[strategy game]] baduk (known in the West as [[Go (board game)|go]]).\n\nThe [[Korea Janggi Association]] is responsible for promoting janggi in South Korea.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Gwangsanghui]] (\u5ee3\u8c61\u6231, \uad11\uc0c1\ud76c)\u2014an 18th-century Janggi variant<ref name=\"\u97e9\u56fd\u53e4\u5178\u7efc\u5408\u6570\u636e\u5e93 \u300a\u4a13\u6df5\u96c6\u00b7\u5ee3\u8c61\u6231\u5fd7\u300b\">{{cite web|url=http://db.itkc.or.kr/index.jsp?bizName=MM&url=/itkcdb/text/nodeViewIframe.jsp?bizName=MM&seojiId=kc_mm_a513&gunchaId=av027&muncheId=01&finId=021&NodeId=&setid=2526027&Pos=0&TotalCount=11&searchUrl=ok|title=<span lang=\"zh\">\u97e9\u56fd\u53e4\u5178\u7efc\u5408\u6570\u636e\u5e93 \u300a\u4a13\u6df5\u96c6\u00b7\u5ee3\u8c61\u6231\u5fd7\u300b</span>|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130423124005/http://db.itkc.or.kr/index.jsp?bizName=MM&url=/itkcdb/text/nodeViewIframe.jsp%3FbizName=MM&seojiId=kc_mm_a513&gunchaId=av027&muncheId=01&finId=021&NodeId=&setid=2526027&Pos=0&TotalCount=11&searchUrl=ok |archive-date=2013-04-23 }}</ref>\n*[[List of Korea-related topics]]\n*[[Xiangqi]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite magazine\n |last=Maynard\n |first=Malcolm\n |title=Janggi: The Chess of Korea\n |editor=Kerry Handscomb\n |publisher=Carpe Diem Publishing\n |magazine=Abstract Games\n |date=Winter 2002\n |issue=12\n |pages=6\u201311\n |issn=1492-0492}}\n*{{cite magazine\n |last=Maynard\n |first=Malcolm\n |title=Janggi: Addenda\n |editor=Kerry Han